/tr/sirkethaberleri/holding/ilke-ozyuksel-mustafa-v-koc-spor-odulunun-sahibi-oldu-/653360 |newspaper=[[Anadolu News Agency]] |title=\u0130lke \u00d6zy\u00fcksel, \"Mustafa V. Ko\u00e7 Spor \u00d6d\u00fcl\u00fc\"n\u00fcn sahibi oldu  |date=25 September 2019 |language=tr |accessdate=28 September 2019 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"m1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.milliyet.com.tr/skorer/ilke-ozyukselden-bronz-madalya-2489342 |newspaper=[[Milliyet]] |title=\u0130lke \u00d6zy\u00fcksel'den bronz madalya! |date=22 July 2017 |language=tr |accessdate=28 September 2019 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{UIPM}} <!--uses Wikidata-->\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ozyuksel, Ilke}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Turkish female modern pentathletes]]\n[[Category:Modern pentathletes at the 2014 Summer Youth Olympics]]\n[[Category:Modern pentathletes at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic modern pentathletes of Turkey]]\n", "name_user": "Kayhan Yavuz", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePrivate life:correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C4%B0lke_%C3%96zy%C3%BCksel"}
{"title_page": "Veer (2010 film)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Veer: An Epic Love Story of a Warrior\n| image          = Veer movie poster.jpg\n| alt            = <!-- see WP:ALT -->\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Anil Sharma]]\n| producer       = \n| screenplay     = Shailash Verma<br />Shaktimaan Talwar\n| story          = [[Salman Khan]]\n| starring       = [[Salman Khan]]<br />[[Zareen Khan]]<br />[[Mithun Chakraborty]]<br /> [[Jackie Shroff]]<br />[[Sohail Khan]]\n| music          = [[Sajid-Wajid]]\n| editing        = Ashfaque Makrani\n| studio         = Eros Entertainment\n| distributor    = [[Eros Entertainment]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2010|1|22}}\n| runtime        = 164 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Hindi\n| budget         = {{INR}}50 crore\n| gross          = {{Estimation}} {{INR}}64.71 crore\n| Director       = [[Anil Sharma]]\n}}\n'''''Veer: An Epic Love Story of a Warrior''''' ({{trans|Brave}}) is a 2010 [[India]]n [[Hindi]]-language [[epic film|epic]] [[action film]] directed by [[Anil Sharma]], and starring [[Salman Khan]],  [[Zareen Khan]], [[Mithun Chakraborty]], [[Jackie Shroff]], [[Sohail Khan]], Rishabh Jain.\n\n==Plot==\nVeer Pratap Singh ([[Salman Khan]]) is a [[Pindari]] prince and the son of the great Pindari warrior, Prithvi Singh ([[Mithun Chakraborty]]), who was known for his great battles to free [[India]] from [[British Raj|British rule]]. Veer wishes to continue his father's legacy by leading a movement of Pindaris against the British in order to free both the [[Rajasthani people|Rajasthani]] Kingdom of Madhavghar and the rest of India from the great colonial power. Veer receives the help of his younger brother, Punya Singh ([[Sohail Khan]]) in gathering an army. However Veer finds opposition from the King of Madhavghar, Gyanendra Singh ([[Jackie Shroff]]), who sees Veer as a threat to Madhavghar and his rule and orders for Veer to be killed. Veer and Punya along with their supporters go into hiding within the [[Thar Desert]] of Rajasthan, while Singh makes an alliance with the British Governor of Rajasthan, James Fraser ([[Tim James Lawrence]]), saying that Madhavghar will support the British in crushing the Pindari movement and eliminating Veer.\n\nTo keep stakes high, the Pindaris kidnap Singh's daughter Princess Yashodhara ([[Zareen Khan]]), who Veer finds himself in love with. The Pindaris then make a failed attempt to take down Singh's palace by surprise. However Singh's spies discover the plan and thousands of Pindari warriors are slaughtered. Veer fails to get his revenge on the corrupt King but knows that Punya has been captured by Yashodhara's brother Gajendra ([[Puru Raaj Kumar]]) as Veer runs in to save his brother and kills Gajendra's men but Gajendra is killed to when he gets punched by Veer and lands on a sword which Gyanendra seeks revenge for his son. In the meantime, Lady Angela Fraser ([[Lisa Lazarus]]), wife of James Fraser, begins to question her husband's actions as he supports the evil king in slaughtering members of the Pindari movement. Fraser refuses to back down from his campaign of crushing the movement.\n\nAfter Veer promises his father that he will finish Singh, he gatecrashes Yashodhara's [[Swayamvara]]. As he takes the princess away from the fort, Gyanendra Singh sees a vast army of Pindaris has surrounded his fort. He asks the British to help him but they refuse and make the Pindaris their ally in a bid to escape from Madhavghar. Before the British leave a battle follows in which the Governor and Gyanendra Singh are killed. Veer, wounded from a gunshot, falls unconscious in the arms of his father. Years later it is shown that Veer's son and Prithvi are having a friendly fight.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Salman Khan]] as Veer Pratap Singh/Veera (Duel role)\n* [[Zareen Khan]] as Princess Yashodhara\n* [[Mithun Chakraborty]] as Prithvi Singh, Veer's Father\n* [[Jackie Shroff]] as Gyanendra Singh, King of Madhavghar and Father of Yashodhara\n* [[Sohail Khan]] as Punya Pratap Singh, Veer's Brother\n* Raj Premi as one of the villains\n* Rishabh Jain as Radhurath, Veer's friend\n* [[Puru Raaj Kumar]] as Gajendra Singh, the prince of Madhavghar, brother to Yashodhara and son to Gyanendra.\n* [[Lisa Lazarus]] as Lady Angela Fraser, wife of Governor James Fraser\n* [[Tim Lawrence]] as James Fraser, Governor General of [[Rajasthan]]\n*[[Karmveer Choudhary]] as Mantri of Jackie Shroff\n* [[Khurram Tejrar]]\n* [[Gita Soto]]\n* [[Neena Gupta]] as Veer's mother\n* [[Aryan Vaid]]\n* [[Bharat Dabholkar]]\n* [[Bunny Anand]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://entertainment.oneindia.in/bollywood/news/2009/salman-saved-bunny-231109.html |title= Salman saved Bunny Anand's life |author= Subhadeep Bhattacharjee |date= 23 November 2009|publisher=One India.com |accessdate=11 February 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Shahbaz Khan (actor)|Shahbaz Khan]] as Naunihal\n* [[Militza Radmilovic]]\n* [[Charissa Glidden]] as the Governess\n* [[Roy Bronsgeest]] as Rhino<ref>Manohar Charla. [http://www.bollyspice.com/view.php/4156-i-fight-veer-to-win-the-princess-roy-bronsgeest.html \"'I Fight Veer to Win the Princess!' \u2013 Roy Bronsgeest\"], BollySpice.com, 21 January 2010 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100124092842/http://www.bollyspice.com/view.php/4156-i-fight-veer-to-win-the-princess-roy-bronsgeest.html |date=24 January 2010 }}</ref>\n* [[Taylor Wright]]\n* [[Luke Groves]]\n* [[Fiona Grace (Jaya Gupta)|Fiona Grace]] as Nina Frances\n* [[Christoph Beiter]] as English soldier\n* [[Clay Mohr]] as English Sergeant.\n* [[Raj Khatri]] as Gyanendra Singh's Senapati.\n* Ajay Kalyansingh as Arab prince\n\n==Production==\nThe story was written by Salman Khan twenty years ago,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/movie_Story.aspx?id=ENTEN20090118222|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120710112842/http://movies.ndtv.com/movie_Story.aspx?id=ENTEN20090118222|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 July 2012|title=Salman Khan's 'Veer' on January 22|date= 24 November 2009|work=Press Trust of India|accessdate=19 April 2010}}</ref> who described it as his dream project.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://veerblogs.erosentertainment.com/index.asp?Page=5 |title= My Dream Project ...VEER |author= Salman Khan |date= 24 November 2009 |work= Official Blog by Salman Khan|publisher= Eros Entertainment |accessdate=21 January 2010}}</ref> At that time, Khan planned to direct the film himself and cast [[Sanjay Dutt]] in the lead role.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.indianexpress.com/news/when-men-were-men/564691/ |title= When Men Were Men |date= 8 January 2010 |work= Indian Express |accessdate=27 January 2010}}</ref> ''Veer'' is also partly based on the [[Russian literature|Russian]] novel ''[[Taras Bulba]]'' by [[Nikolai Gogol]].<ref name=rediff>{{cite web |url= http://movies.rediff.com/slide-show/2010/jan/08/slide-show-1-salman-khan-on-veer.htm |title= 'I don't want to make depressing films for my fans' |author= Firdaus Ashraf, Syed |date= 8 January 2009 |publisher= Rediff.com |accessdate=21 January 2010}}</ref> For his role as Veer, Salman Khan went on a special diet and worked out with a personal trainer.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.apunkachoice.com/scoop/bollywood/20080805-3.html |title= Salman Khan gets brawnier for 'Veer' |author= Aparajita Ghosh |date= 5 April 2008 |publisher=ApunkaChoice.com |accessdate=26 January 2010}}</ref> For her role as a 19th-century princess, [[Zarine Khan]] put on eight kilos of extra weight.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://entertainment.oneindia.in/bollywood/gupshup/2009/zarine-put-on-weight-161209.html |title= Salman made Zarine Khan gain weight |author= Subhadeep Bhattacharjee |date= 16 December 2009 |publisher=One India |accessdate=27 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nPrincipal photography for ''Veer'' began on 1 December 2008. Portions of the film were originally scheduled to be shot at the [[College of Engineering, Pune|College of Engineering]] and the Agricultural College in [[Pune]], but due to the [[2009 flu pandemic in India|swine flu outbreak]] the locations were moved to Mumbai.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.mid-day.com/entertainment/2009/aug/120809-Salman-Khan-Veer-Five-day-shoot-cancelled-Swine-Flu-scare-Pune-Bollywood.htm |title= Swine flu, they fled! |work= Mid Day |accessdate=27 January 2010}}</ref> Other location shooting took place in Jaipur and [[Bikaner]]. Location shooting at [[Amber Fort]] in [[Jaipur]] was also interrupted when several onlookers were injured and the [[Rajasthan High Court]] ordered a halt to filming. A case was filed against Anil Sharma accusing the film crew of damaging the fort, violating several conservation laws and causing the structure's 500-year-old roof to collapse.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-02-17/jaipur/28058122_1_film-unit-anil-sharma-cjm-court |title= Case against Amber bosses,'Veer' unit |date= 17 February 2009 |work= Times of India |accessdate=27 January 2010}}</ref> The crew finished their shoot after paying Rs. 2&nbsp;million in damages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screenindia.com/news/salman-given-a-second-chance-to-shoot-veer-at-amber-fort/425673/ |title=Salman given a second chance to shoot 'Veer' at Amber Fort |date=19 February 2009 |work=Screen |accessdate=27 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630023741/http://www.screenindia.com/news/salman-given-a-second-chance-to-shoot-veer-at-amber-fort/425673 |archivedate=30 June 2009 }}</ref>\n\n[[Rochester Castle]] appears as a backdrop for a  musical sequence named 'Everytime I look into your eyes I see my paradise' featuring a horse and carriage. The [[Chatham Dockyard]] provided the setting for many of the montage shots used in the UK dance sequences as well as the location where Veer first meets  Yuvraji Yashodhara.<ref>{{cite web|author=Kent Film Office|url=http://kentfilmoffice.co.uk/2010/02/veer-2010/|title=Kent Film Office Veer Film Focus}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 January 2010, author Pavan Chaudhary filed a Rs. 2 million suit against Khan, Anil Sharma and producer Vijay Kumar Galani, alleging that the film borrowed elements from his novel, ''Trilogy of Wisdom''. The suit called for a halt of the film's screenings.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/article94721.ece |title= Court notice to Veer Salman over copyright violation |date= 25 January 2010 |work= The Hindu |accessdate=26 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://movies.indiatimes.com/news-gossip/news/Court-to-hear-lawsuit-against-Veer-Monday/articleshow/5497390.cms |title= Court to hear lawsuit against 'Veer' Monday |date= 25 January 2010 |work= Indiatimes |accessdate= 26 January 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100129003458/http://movies.indiatimes.com/news-gossip/news/Court-to-hear-lawsuit-against-Veer-Monday/articleshow/5497390.cms |archive-date= 29 January 2010 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Marketing==\nThe trailer of ''Veer'' was released on 27 November 2009 at the screening of [[Priyadarshan]]'s ''[[De Dana Dan]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/Salmans-Veer-releases-on-Jan-22/articleshow/5263538.cms |title=Salman's Veer releases on Jan 22 |date=24 November 2009 |work=Times of India |accessdate=6 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091207022108/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/Salmans-Veer-releases-on-Jan-22/articleshow/5263538.cms |archivedate=7 December 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical reception===\nThe movie was generally panned by critics.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=1453&nCat=box_office_report |title=Veer had a bumper first day at single screens |publisher=BoxOffice India |accessdate=22 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603201231/http://boxofficeindia.com/boxdetail.php?page=shownews |archivedate=3 June 2013 }}</ref> [[Taran Adarsh]] criticized the writing and direction of the movie, describing it as a colossal disappointment.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sify.com/movies/bollywood/review.php?id=14928427&ctid=5&cid=2425|title=Review: Veer is a colossal disappointment!|publisher=[[Sify]]|accessdate=22 January 2010}}</ref> [[Rajeev Masand]] of [[CNN-IBN]] termed it as \"an impossible film to appreciate\", criticizing the performance of the support cast, while praising the performance of Salman Khan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/masand-movie-review-veer-is-an-impossible-film/109075-8.html?from=webx|title=Masand Movie Review: Veer is an impossible film|publisher=[[CNN IBN]]|accessdate=22 January 2010}}</ref> Gaurav Malani praised the performance of Salman Khan, while terming the story as average.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://movies.indiatimes.com/reviews/bollywood/Veer-Movie-Review/articleshow/5485098.cms|title=Director: Anil Sharma Cast: Salman Khan, Zarine Khan Rating:** Veer: Movie Review|publisher=[[Times of India]]|accessdate=22 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100125144706/http://movies.indiatimes.com/reviews/bollywood/Veer-Movie-Review/articleshow/5485098.cms|archive-date=25 January 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Noyon Jyoti Parasara of AOL.in also praised Salman Khan but added \"Overall, 'Veer' has its pluses but it is sadly restricted to a very average film. It has nothing new and that only makes it seem slower.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aol.in/bollywood-story/veer-movie-review/760211 |title=Rating:**1/2 Veer: Movie Review |publisher=[[AOL]].in |accessdate=22 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100131094243/http://www.aol.in/bollywood-story/veer-movie-review/760211 |archivedate=31 January 2010 }}</ref>\n\nAmong U.S. critics, [[Frank Lovece]] of ''[[Film Journal International]]'' enjoyed it as \"hokum of the highest order, punctuated with the most rousing musical sequences of the last several Indian imports,\" and after dissecting the film's numerous historical and chronological fallacies said, \"Stateside Bollywood fans more accustomed to modern-day musical romances or stylish crime thrillers will be pleasantly surprised to find a period piece that's more ''[[Xena: Warrior Princess]]'' than ''[[A Passage to India]]''.<ref>[[Frank Lovece|Lovece, Frank]]. [http://www.filmjournal.com/filmjournal/content_display/reviews/specialty-releases/e3i337ac1235d0161b867308f46e57928af ''Veer'' (review)], ''[[Film Journal International]]'' , 25 January 2010</ref>\n\n===Criticism by Rajput community===\nThe [[Rajput]] youth organisation [[Kalyan Singh Kalvi|Karni Sena]] was heavily critical of ''Veer'', alleging that portions of the dialogue are \"derogatory and demeaning for the Rajput community\". Members of the group attacked several multiplexes in Jaipur, vandalising posters and smashing windows. Anil Sharma responded that it was a misunderstanding and no insult had been intended towards the Rajput community.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-02-01/news-interviews/28149455_1_rajput-karni-sena-anil-sharma |title=Sallu's Veer in trouble |author= Divya Kaushik and Shweta Thakur |date= 1 February 2010 |work= Times of India |accessdate=31 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\nAccording to Eros, ''Veer'' grossed Rs 410&nbsp;million nett in its first week in India.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report_despite-poor-reviews-salman-s-veer-is-steady-at-the-box-office_1339912 |title= Despite poor review, Salman's Veer steady at box office |author= Press Trust India |date= 27 January 2010 |work= Daily News & Analysis |accessdate=27 January 2010}}</ref>\nVeer netted a lifetime of Rs 375.2&nbsp;million (Rs 497.5&nbsp;million gross) in India and was the 9th highest-grossing film domestically of 2010.<ref>[http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=317&catName=MjAxMC0yMDE5 Boxofficeindia.com] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014094622/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=317&catName=MjAxMC0yMDE5 |date=14 October 2013 }}</ref>\n\nVeer has a worldwide lifetime gross of Rs 585.8&nbsp;million ($12,600,000).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=348&catName=TGlmZXRpbWUgV29ybGR3aWRlIEluIFVTICQ= |accessdate=11 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020075613/http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=348&catName=TGlmZXRpbWUgV29ybGR3aWRlIEluIFVTICQ= |archivedate=20 October 2013|title=Boxofficeindia.com }}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n;[[Zee Cine Awards|2011 Zee Cine Awards]]\n* Nominated \u2013 [[Zee Cine Award for Best Female Debut|Best Female Debut]] \u2013 [[Zarine Khan]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Nominations for Zee Cine Awards 2011 |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/features/2011/01/01/6977/index.html |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |accessdate=7 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110105041016/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/features/2011/01/01/6977/index.html |archivedate=5 January 2011 }}</ref>\n\n;[[3rd Mirchi Music Awards]]\n* Nominated \u2013 [[Mirchi Music Award for Lyricist of The Year|Lyricist of The Year]] \u2013 [[Gulzar]] for \"Surili Akhiyon Wale\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.radiomirchi.com/mma2010/hindi/nominees.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110130070949/http://www.radiomirchi.com/mma2010/hindi/nominees.php|url-status=dead|archive-date=2011-01-30|title=Nominees - Mirchi Music Award Hindi 2010|date=2011-01-30|access-date=2018-09-30}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Veer\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Sajid (music director)|Sajid]]- [[Sajid-Wajid|Wajid]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|df=yes|2009|12|17}}\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film soundtrack]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Eros Music]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\nThe film's music was released on 17 December 2009. The film's songs are composed by [[Sajid\u2013Wajid]] and the lyrics are written by lyricist [[Gulzar]].\n\nMusic critic Joginder Tuteja of [[Bollywood Hungama]] gave it an overall rating of 3.5 out of 5.<ref name=\"Bh\"/> The songs, ''Surili Akhiyon Wale'', ''Salaam Aaya'' and ''Taali'' received special praise.<ref name=\"Bh\">{{cite web |url= http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/musicreview/13908/index.html |title= Veer: Music Review |author= Joginder Tutega |date= 21 December 2009 |publisher= Bollywood Hungama |accessdate=21 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Artist(s)\n| title1 = Meherbaniyan | extra1 = [[Sonu Nigam]] | length1 = 4:29\n| title2 = Taali | extra2 = Sonu Nigam, [[Sukhwinder Singh]], [[Sajid-Wajid|Wajid]], [[Neuman Pinto]] | length2 = 6:10\n| title3 = Surili Akhiyon Wale | extra3 = [[Rahat Fateh Ali Khan]], [[Suzanne D'Mello]] | length3 = 5:31\n| title4 = Kanha (Thumari) | extra4 = [[Rekha Bhardwaj]], [[Sharib Sabri]], [[Toshi Sabri]], [[Shabab Sabri]] | length4 = 4:36\n| title5 = Taali | extra5 = Sukhwinder Singh | length5 = 6:01\n| title6 = Surili Akhiyon Wale | extra6 = Rahat Fateh Ali Khan, [[Sunidhi Chauhan]], Suzanne D'Mello | length6 = 5:23\n| title7 = Salaam Aaya | extra7 = [[Roop Kumar Rathod]], [[Shreya Ghoshal]], Suzanne D'Mello | length7 = 4:45\n| title8 = Spirit of Veer | note8 = Instrumental | length8 = 0:58\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|India|Film|Bollywood}}\n\n[[List of historical drama films of Asia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|1185412}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|10012133_veer}}\n* {{Mojo title|veer2010}}\n{{commons category|Veer (2010 film)}}\n{{Taras Bulba}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Veer}}\n[[Category:2010 films]]\n[[Category:2010s action films]]\n[[Category:2010s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian epic films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian action films]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by Nikolai Gogol]]\n[[Category:Films set in India]]\n[[Category:Films shot in India]]\n[[Category:Films shot in London]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1820s]]\n[[Category:2010s historical drama films]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 19th century]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1825]]\n[[Category:Indian historical drama films]]\n[[Category:Period action films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Veer: An Epic Love Story of a Warrior\n| image          = Veer movie poster.jpg\n| alt            = <!-- see WP:ALT -->\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Anil Sharma]]\n| producer       = \n| screenplay     = Shailash Verma<br />Shaktimaan Talwar\n| story          = [[Salman Khan]]\n| starring       = [[Salman Khan]]<br />[[Zareen Khan]]<br />[[Mithun Chakraborty]]<br /> [[Jackie Shroff]]<br />[[Sohail Khan]]\n| music          = [[Sajid-Wajid]]\n| editing        = Ashfaque Makrani\n| studio         = Eros Entertainment\n| distributor    = [[Eros Entertainment]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2010|1|22}}\n| runtime        = 164 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Hindi\n| budget         = {{INR}}50 crore\n| gross          = {{Estimation}} {{INR}}64.71 crore\n| Director       = [[Anil Sharma]]\n}}\n'''''Veer: An Epic Love Story of a Warrior''''' ({{trans|Brave}}) is a 2010 [[India]]n [[Hindi]]-language [[epic film|epic]] [[action film]] directed by [[Anil Sharma]], and starring [[Salman Khan]],  [[Zareen Khan]], [[Mithun Chakraborty]], [[Jackie Shroff]], [[Sohail Khan]], Rishabh Jain.\n\n==Plot==\nVeer Pratap Singh ([[Salman Khan]]) is a [[Pindari]] prince and the son of the great Pindari warrior, Prithvi Singh ([[Mithun Chakraborty]]), who was known for his great battles to free [[India]] from [[British Raj|British rule]]. Veer wishes to continue his father's legacy by leading a movement of Pindaris against the British in order to free both the [[Rajasthani people|Rajasthani]] Kingdom of Madhavghar and the rest of India from the great colonial power. Veer receives the help of his younger brother, Punya Singh ([[Sohail Khan]]) in gathering an army. However Veer finds opposition from the King of Madhavghar, Gyanendra Singh ([[Jackie Shroff]]), who sees Veer as a threat to Madhavghar and his rule and orders for Veer to be killed. Veer and Punya along with their supporters go into hiding within the [[Thar Desert]] of Rajasthan, while Singh makes an alliance with the British Governor of Rajasthan, James Fraser ([[Tim James Lawrence]]), saying that Madhavghar will support the British in crushing the Pindari movement and eliminating Veer.\n\nTo keep stakes high, the Pindaris kidnap Singh's daughter Princess Yashodhara ([[Zareen Khan]]), who Veer finds himself in love with. The Pindaris then make a failed attempt to take down Singh's palace by surprise. However Singh's spies discover the plan and thousands of Pindari warriors are slaughtered. Veer fails to get his revenge on the corrupt King but knows that Punya has been captured by Yashodhara's brother Gajendra ([[Puru Raaj Kumar]]) as Veer runs in to save his brother and kills Gajendra's men but Gajendra is killed to when he gets punched by Veer and lands on a sword which Gyanendra seeks revenge for his son. In the meantime, Lady Angela Fraser ([[Lisa Lazarus]]), wife of James Fraser, begins to question her husband's actions as he supports the evil king in slaughtering members of the Pindari movement. Fraser refuses to back down from his campaign of crushing the movement.\n\nAfter Veer promises his father that he will finish Singh, he gatecrashes Yashodhara's [[Swayamvara]]. As he takes the princess away from the fort, Gyanendra Singh sees a vast army of Pindaris has surrounded his fort. He asks the British to help him but they refuse and make the Pindaris their ally in a bid to escape from Madhavghar. Before the British leave a battle follows in which the Governor and Gyanendra Singh are killed. Veer, wounded from a gunshot, falls unconscious in the arms of his father. Years later it is shown that Veer's son and Prithvi are having a friendly fight.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Salman Khan]] as Veer Pratap Singh/Veera(Duel role)\n* [[Zareen Khan]] as Princess Yashodhara\n* [[Mithun Chakraborty]] as Prithvi Singh, Veer's Father\n* [[Jackie Shroff]] as Gyanendra Singh, King of Madhavghar and Father of Yashodhara\n* [[Sohail Khan]] as Punya Pratap Singh, Veer's Brother\n* Raj Premi as one of the villains\n* Rishabh Jain as Radhurath, Veer's friend\n* [[Puru Raaj Kumar]] as Gajendra Singh, the prince of Madhavghar, brother to Yashodhara and son to Gyanendra.\n* [[Lisa Lazarus]] as Lady Angela Fraser, wife of Governor James Fraser\n* [[Tim Lawrence]] as James Fraser, Governor General of [[Rajasthan]]\n*[[Karmveer Choudhary]] as Mantri of Jackie Shroff\n* [[Khurram Tejrar]]\n* [[Gita Soto]]\n* [[Neena Gupta]] as Veer's mother\n* [[Aryan Vaid]]\n* [[Bharat Dabholkar]]\n* [[Bunny Anand]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://entertainment.oneindia.in/bollywood/news/2009/salman-saved-bunny-231109.html |title= Salman saved Bunny Anand's life |author= Subhadeep Bhattacharjee |date= 23 November 2009|publisher=One India.com |accessdate=11 February 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Shahbaz Khan (actor)|Shahbaz Khan]] as Naunihal\n* [[Militza Radmilovic]]\n* [[Charissa Glidden]] as the Governess\n* [[Roy Bronsgeest]] as Rhino<ref>Manohar Charla. [http://www.bollyspice.com/view.php/4156-i-fight-veer-to-win-the-princess-roy-bronsgeest.html \"'I Fight Veer to Win the Princess!' \u2013 Roy Bronsgeest\"], BollySpice.com, 21 January 2010 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100124092842/http://www.bollyspice.com/view.php/4156-i-fight-veer-to-win-the-princess-roy-bronsgeest.html |date=24 January 2010 }}</ref>\n* [[Taylor Wright]]\n* [[Luke Groves]]\n* [[Fiona Grace (Jaya Gupta)|Fiona Grace]] as Nina Frances\n* [[Christoph Beiter]] as English soldier\n* [[Clay Mohr]] as English Sergeant.\n* [[Raj Khatri]] as Gyanendra Singh's Senapati.\n* Ajay Kalyansingh as Arab prince\n\n==Production==\nThe story was written by Salman Khan twenty years ago,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/movie_Story.aspx?id=ENTEN20090118222|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120710112842/http://movies.ndtv.com/movie_Story.aspx?id=ENTEN20090118222|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 July 2012|title=Salman Khan's 'Veer' on January 22|date= 24 November 2009|work=Press Trust of India|accessdate=19 April 2010}}</ref> who described it as his dream project.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://veerblogs.erosentertainment.com/index.asp?Page=5 |title= My Dream Project ...VEER |author= Salman Khan |date= 24 November 2009 |work= Official Blog by Salman Khan|publisher= Eros Entertainment |accessdate=21 January 2010}}</ref> At that time, Khan planned to direct the film himself and cast [[Sanjay Dutt]] in the lead role.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.indianexpress.com/news/when-men-were-men/564691/ |title= When Men Were Men |date= 8 January 2010 |work= Indian Express |accessdate=27 January 2010}}</ref> ''Veer'' is also partly based on the [[Russian literature|Russian]] novel ''[[Taras Bulba]]'' by [[Nikolai Gogol]].<ref name=rediff>{{cite web |url= http://movies.rediff.com/slide-show/2010/jan/08/slide-show-1-salman-khan-on-veer.htm |title= 'I don't want to make depressing films for my fans' |author= Firdaus Ashraf, Syed |date= 8 January 2009 |publisher= Rediff.com |accessdate=21 January 2010}}</ref> For his role as Veer, Salman Khan went on a special diet and worked out with a personal trainer.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.apunkachoice.com/scoop/bollywood/20080805-3.html |title= Salman Khan gets brawnier for 'Veer' |author= Aparajita Ghosh |date= 5 April 2008 |publisher=ApunkaChoice.com |accessdate=26 January 2010}}</ref> For her role as a 19th-century princess, [[Zarine Khan]] put on eight kilos of extra weight.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://entertainment.oneindia.in/bollywood/gupshup/2009/zarine-put-on-weight-161209.html |title= Salman made Zarine Khan gain weight |author= Subhadeep Bhattacharjee |date= 16 December 2009 |publisher=One India |accessdate=27 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nPrincipal photography for ''Veer'' began on 1 December 2008. Portions of the film were originally scheduled to be shot at the [[College of Engineering, Pune|College of Engineering]] and the Agricultural College in [[Pune]], but due to the [[2009 flu pandemic in India|swine flu outbreak]] the locations were moved to Mumbai.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.mid-day.com/entertainment/2009/aug/120809-Salman-Khan-Veer-Five-day-shoot-cancelled-Swine-Flu-scare-Pune-Bollywood.htm |title= Swine flu, they fled! |work= Mid Day |accessdate=27 January 2010}}</ref> Other location shooting took place in Jaipur and [[Bikaner]]. Location shooting at [[Amber Fort]] in [[Jaipur]] was also interrupted when several onlookers were injured and the [[Rajasthan High Court]] ordered a halt to filming. A case was filed against Anil Sharma accusing the film crew of damaging the fort, violating several conservation laws and causing the structure's 500-year-old roof to collapse.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-02-17/jaipur/28058122_1_film-unit-anil-sharma-cjm-court |title= Case against Amber bosses,'Veer' unit |date= 17 February 2009 |work= Times of India |accessdate=27 January 2010}}</ref> The crew finished their shoot after paying Rs. 2&nbsp;million in damages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screenindia.com/news/salman-given-a-second-chance-to-shoot-veer-at-amber-fort/425673/ |title=Salman given a second chance to shoot 'Veer' at Amber Fort |date=19 February 2009 |work=Screen |accessdate=27 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630023741/http://www.screenindia.com/news/salman-given-a-second-chance-to-shoot-veer-at-amber-fort/425673 |archivedate=30 June 2009 }}</ref>\n\n[[Rochester Castle]] appears as a backdrop for a  musical sequence named 'Everytime I look into your eyes I see my paradise' featuring a horse and carriage. The [[Chatham Dockyard]] provided the setting for many of the montage shots used in the UK dance sequences as well as the location where Veer first meets  Yuvraji Yashodhara.<ref>{{cite web|author=Kent Film Office|url=http://kentfilmoffice.co.uk/2010/02/veer-2010/|title=Kent Film Office Veer Film Focus}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 January 2010, author Pavan Chaudhary filed a Rs. 2 million suit against Khan, Anil Sharma and producer Vijay Kumar Galani, alleging that the film borrowed elements from his novel, ''Trilogy of Wisdom''. The suit called for a halt of the film's screenings.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/article94721.ece |title= Court notice to Veer Salman over copyright violation |date= 25 January 2010 |work= The Hindu |accessdate=26 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://movies.indiatimes.com/news-gossip/news/Court-to-hear-lawsuit-against-Veer-Monday/articleshow/5497390.cms |title= Court to hear lawsuit against 'Veer' Monday |date= 25 January 2010 |work= Indiatimes |accessdate= 26 January 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100129003458/http://movies.indiatimes.com/news-gossip/news/Court-to-hear-lawsuit-against-Veer-Monday/articleshow/5497390.cms |archive-date= 29 January 2010 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Marketing==\nThe trailer of ''Veer'' was released on 27 November 2009 at the screening of [[Priyadarshan]]'s ''[[De Dana Dan]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/Salmans-Veer-releases-on-Jan-22/articleshow/5263538.cms |title=Salman's Veer releases on Jan 22 |date=24 November 2009 |work=Times of India |accessdate=6 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091207022108/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/Salmans-Veer-releases-on-Jan-22/articleshow/5263538.cms |archivedate=7 December 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical reception===\nThe movie was generally panned by critics.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=1453&nCat=box_office_report |title=Veer had a bumper first day at single screens |publisher=BoxOffice India |accessdate=22 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603201231/http://boxofficeindia.com/boxdetail.php?page=shownews |archivedate=3 June 2013 }}</ref> [[Taran Adarsh]] criticized the writing and direction of the movie, describing it as a colossal disappointment.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sify.com/movies/bollywood/review.php?id=14928427&ctid=5&cid=2425|title=Review: Veer is a colossal disappointment!|publisher=[[Sify]]|accessdate=22 January 2010}}</ref> [[Rajeev Masand]] of [[CNN-IBN]] termed it as \"an impossible film to appreciate\", criticizing the performance of the support cast, while praising the performance of Salman Khan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/masand-movie-review-veer-is-an-impossible-film/109075-8.html?from=webx|title=Masand Movie Review: Veer is an impossible film|publisher=[[CNN IBN]]|accessdate=22 January 2010}}</ref> Gaurav Malani praised the performance of Salman Khan, while terming the story as average.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://movies.indiatimes.com/reviews/bollywood/Veer-Movie-Review/articleshow/5485098.cms|title=Director: Anil Sharma Cast: Salman Khan, Zarine Khan Rating:** Veer: Movie Review|publisher=[[Times of India]]|accessdate=22 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100125144706/http://movies.indiatimes.com/reviews/bollywood/Veer-Movie-Review/articleshow/5485098.cms|archive-date=25 January 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Noyon Jyoti Parasara of AOL.in also praised Salman Khan but added \"Overall, 'Veer' has its pluses but it is sadly restricted to a very average film. It has nothing new and that only makes it seem slower.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aol.in/bollywood-story/veer-movie-review/760211 |title=Rating:**1/2 Veer: Movie Review |publisher=[[AOL]].in |accessdate=22 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100131094243/http://www.aol.in/bollywood-story/veer-movie-review/760211 |archivedate=31 January 2010 }}</ref>\n\nAmong U.S. critics, [[Frank Lovece]] of ''[[Film Journal International]]'' enjoyed it as \"hokum of the highest order, punctuated with the most rousing musical sequences of the last several Indian imports,\" and after dissecting the film's numerous historical and chronological fallacies said, \"Stateside Bollywood fans more accustomed to modern-day musical romances or stylish crime thrillers will be pleasantly surprised to find a period piece that's more ''[[Xena: Warrior Princess]]'' than ''[[A Passage to India]]''.<ref>[[Frank Lovece|Lovece, Frank]]. [http://www.filmjournal.com/filmjournal/content_display/reviews/specialty-releases/e3i337ac1235d0161b867308f46e57928af ''Veer'' (review)], ''[[Film Journal International]]'' , 25 January 2010</ref>\n\n===Criticism by Rajput community===\nThe [[Rajput]] youth organisation [[Kalyan Singh Kalvi|Karni Sena]] was heavily critical of ''Veer'', alleging that portions of the dialogue are \"derogatory and demeaning for the Rajput community\". Members of the group attacked several multiplexes in Jaipur, vandalising posters and smashing windows. Anil Sharma responded that it was a misunderstanding and no insult had been intended towards the Rajput community.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-02-01/news-interviews/28149455_1_rajput-karni-sena-anil-sharma |title=Sallu's Veer in trouble |author= Divya Kaushik and Shweta Thakur |date= 1 February 2010 |work= Times of India |accessdate=31 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\nAccording to Eros, ''Veer'' grossed Rs 410&nbsp;million nett in its first week in India.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report_despite-poor-reviews-salman-s-veer-is-steady-at-the-box-office_1339912 |title= Despite poor review, Salman's Veer steady at box office |author= Press Trust India |date= 27 January 2010 |work= Daily News & Analysis |accessdate=27 January 2010}}</ref>\nVeer netted a lifetime of Rs 375.2&nbsp;million (Rs 497.5&nbsp;million gross) in India and was the 9th highest-grossing film domestically of 2010.<ref>[http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=317&catName=MjAxMC0yMDE5 Boxofficeindia.com] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014094622/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=317&catName=MjAxMC0yMDE5 |date=14 October 2013 }}</ref>\n\nVeer has a worldwide lifetime gross of Rs 585.8&nbsp;million ($12,600,000).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=348&catName=TGlmZXRpbWUgV29ybGR3aWRlIEluIFVTICQ= |accessdate=11 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020075613/http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=348&catName=TGlmZXRpbWUgV29ybGR3aWRlIEluIFVTICQ= |archivedate=20 October 2013|title=Boxofficeindia.com }}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n;[[Zee Cine Awards|2011 Zee Cine Awards]]\n* Nominated \u2013 [[Zee Cine Award for Best Female Debut|Best Female Debut]] \u2013 [[Zarine Khan]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Nominations for Zee Cine Awards 2011 |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/features/2011/01/01/6977/index.html |publisher=Bollywood Hungama |accessdate=7 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110105041016/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/features/2011/01/01/6977/index.html |archivedate=5 January 2011 }}</ref>\n\n;[[3rd Mirchi Music Awards]]\n* Nominated \u2013 [[Mirchi Music Award for Lyricist of The Year|Lyricist of The Year]] \u2013 [[Gulzar]] for \"Surili Akhiyon Wale\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.radiomirchi.com/mma2010/hindi/nominees.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110130070949/http://www.radiomirchi.com/mma2010/hindi/nominees.php|url-status=dead|archive-date=2011-01-30|title=Nominees - Mirchi Music Award Hindi 2010|date=2011-01-30|access-date=2018-09-30}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Veer\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Sajid (music director)|Sajid]]- [[Sajid-Wajid|Wajid]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|df=yes|2009|12|17}}\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film soundtrack]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Eros Music]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\nThe film's music was released on 17 December 2009. The film's songs are composed by [[Sajid\u2013Wajid]] and the lyrics are written by lyricist [[Gulzar]].\n\nMusic critic Joginder Tuteja of [[Bollywood Hungama]] gave it an overall rating of 3.5 out of 5.<ref name=\"Bh\"/> The songs, ''Surili Akhiyon Wale'', ''Salaam Aaya'' and ''Taali'' received special praise.<ref name=\"Bh\">{{cite web |url= http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/musicreview/13908/index.html |title= Veer: Music Review |author= Joginder Tutega |date= 21 December 2009 |publisher= Bollywood Hungama |accessdate=21 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Artist(s)\n| title1 = Meherbaniyan | extra1 = [[Sonu Nigam]] | length1 = 4:29\n| title2 = Taali | extra2 = Sonu Nigam, [[Sukhwinder Singh]], [[Sajid-Wajid|Wajid]], [[Neuman Pinto]] | length2 = 6:10\n| title3 = Surili Akhiyon Wale | extra3 = [[Rahat Fateh Ali Khan]], [[Suzanne D'Mello]] | length3 = 5:31\n| title4 = Kanha (Thumari) | extra4 = [[Rekha Bhardwaj]], [[Sharib Sabri]], [[Toshi Sabri]], [[Shabab Sabri]] | length4 = 4:36\n| title5 = Taali | extra5 = Sukhwinder Singh | length5 = 6:01\n| title6 = Surili Akhiyon Wale | extra6 = Rahat Fateh Ali Khan, [[Sunidhi Chauhan]], Suzanne D'Mello | length6 = 5:23\n| title7 = Salaam Aaya | extra7 = [[Roop Kumar Rathod]], [[Shreya Ghoshal]], Suzanne D'Mello | length7 = 4:45\n| title8 = Spirit of Veer | note8 = Instrumental | length8 = 0:58\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|India|Film|Bollywood}}\n\n[[List of historical drama films of Asia]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|1185412}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|10012133_veer}}\n* {{Mojo title|veer2010}}\n{{commons category|Veer (2010 film)}}\n{{Taras Bulba}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Veer}}\n[[Category:2010 films]]\n[[Category:2010s action films]]\n[[Category:2010s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian epic films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian action films]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by Nikolai Gogol]]\n[[Category:Films set in India]]\n[[Category:Films shot in India]]\n[[Category:Films shot in London]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1820s]]\n[[Category:2010s historical drama films]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 19th century]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1825]]\n[[Category:Indian historical drama films]]\n[[Category:Period action films]]\n", "name_user": "Danielt998", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCast:clean up, replaced: a( \u2192 a (", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Veer_(2010_film)"}
{"title_page": "Dorick M. Wright", "text_new": "{{short description|Belizean Roman Catholic priest}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type        = Bishop\n| honorific-prefix = The Most Reverend\n| name        = Dorick M. Wright, DD\n| title       = Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Belize City-Belmopan|Belize City-Belmopan]]\n| image       =\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| church      = [[Catholic Church]]\n| see         = [[Titular Bishop]] of Thimida Regia\n| appointed   = 18 November 2006\n| term        = 23 January 2007 \u201326  January 2017\n| predecessor = [[Osmond P. Martin]]\n| successor   = \n<!--   Orders   -->\n| ordination     = 27 June 1975\n| ordained_by    = \n| consecration   = 4 April 2002\n| consecrated_by = Bishop [[Osmond P. Martin]]\n| rank           = Auxiliary Bishop of Belize\n<!--   Personal details   -->\n|birth_name=Dorick McGowan Wright\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1945|11|15}}\n| birth_place   = [[Belize City]], [[British Honduras]] (now [[Belize]])\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|2020|4|15|1945|11|15|mf=yes|}}<ref name=breakingbelizenews.com>{{cite web| title =Bishop Dorick Wright passes at age 74|url =https://www.breakingbelizenews.com/2020/04/15/bishop-dorrick-wright-passes-at-age-74/|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n| death_place   = \n| previous_post = }}\n\n'''Dorick McGowan Wright, DD,''' (November 15, 1945 \u2013 April 15, 2020) was a [[Belize]]an prelate. From 2006-2017, he has served as the fourth [[Catholic bishop|bishop]] of the [[Catholic Church]] for the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Belize City-Belmopan]].<ref name=Wright>{{cite web| title =Dorick Wright| url =http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bmcgw.html|accessdate=June 19, 2015}}</ref> Pope Francis accepted his resignation on 26 January 2017 and appointed Fr. {{interlanguage link|Lawrence Sydney Nicasio|de}} as the new Bishop.\n\n==Early life==\n\nWright grew up in [[Holy Redeemer Cathedral]] parish in what was then [[British Honduras]]. His first cousin was [[Anglican church|Anglican]] bishop [[Philip S. Wright|Philip Wright]] and his uncle was Pastor Lloyd Wright from Bethel [[Assemblies of God|Assembly of God]] Church.<ref>{{cite web| title =LLoyd Wright| url =http://www.anglicannews.org/news/2005/10/new-bishop-for-the-diocese-of-belize.aspx|accessdate=June 19, 2015}}</ref> In 1961, while in his mid-teens, he lost his mother, two sisters, and a brother in [[hurricane Hattie]]. The tree image on Bishop Wright\u2019s coat of arms is symbolic of the mango tree that saved his life. He attended [[St. John's College, Belize|St. John\u2019s College]] and then taught for three years at [[Holy Redeemer Primary School]]. He then entered [[Conception Abbey|Conception Seminary]], run by the [[Order of St. Benedict]] in north-west [[Missouri]], where he completed his education for the priesthood.<ref name=woods>Woods, Charles M. Sr., et al. ''Years of Grace: The History of Roman Catholic Evangelization in Belize: 1524-2014.'' (Belize: Roman Catholic Diocese of Belize City-Belmopan, 2015), pp. 305f.</ref>\n\n==Episcopacy==\n\nWright was ordained at [[Holy Redeemer Cathedral]], Belize City, on June 27, 1975. He then assisted at St. Joseph Parish, [[Holy Redeemer Catholic Parish, Belize City|Holy Redeemer Cathedral parish]], and Inmaculada Parish in Orange Walk. He returned to St. Joseph Parish as pastor and then to Holy Redeemer Cathedral. On April 4, 2002, Wright was consecrated at St. John\u2019s College as [[Auxiliary bishop|Auxiliary]] to Bishop [[Osmond P. Martin]], with Martin the principal consecrator. He was appointed bishop of the diocese on November 18, 2006, and installed on January 23, 2007, with Archbishop [[Luigi Pezzuto]], [[nuncio]] for Belize and [[El Salvador]], presiding.<ref name=woods/>\n\nBishop Wright founded St. Benedict Diocesan Seminary, a minor seminary offering two years of college training to those studying for the priesthood. It opened on August 27, 2013, on the grounds of the former Santa Familia [[Benedictine]] Monastery outside [[San Ignacio, Belize|Santa Elena]], Belize. Four young men comprised its first class.<ref>{{cite web| title =Seminary| url =http://catholic.bz/v1/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=129:new-diocesan-seminary&catid=1:latest-news&Itemid=18| accessdate =June 19, 2015| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20150427111333/http://catholic.bz/v1/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=129:new-diocesan-seminary&catid=1:latest-news&Itemid=18| archive-date =April 27, 2015| url-status =dead}}</ref>\n\nWright outspokenly opposed some aspects of the government\u2019s 2013 promotion of [[sexual orientation|same-sex-orientation]] rights. His position was supported by the Belize Evangelical Council, and later also by the Belize Council of Churches that included the [[Roman Catholic Church in Belize]] as a member.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.refworld.org/pdfid/50af2ee72.pdf|title=Country-of-origin information to support the adjudication of asylum claims from Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender and Intersex (\u2018LGBTI\u2019) asylum-seekers|last=|first=|date=November 14, 2012|website=Asylum Research Consultancy|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> With Bishop Wright\u2019s eyesight failing, he requested help to carry out his mission and in 2012 [[Viatorian]] Fr. [[Christopher Glancy]] was consecrated Auxiliary Bishop and [[Vicar General]] for the Diocese of Belize City-Belmopan.<ref name=Wright/>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wright, Dorick}}\n[[Category:Roman Catholic bishops in Belize]]\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Roman Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:Belizean clergy]]\n[[Category:Belizean Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:People from Belize City]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Belizean Roman Catholic priest}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type        = Bishop\n| honorific-prefix = The Most Reverend\n| name        = Dorick M. Wright, DD\n| title       = Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Belize City-Belmopan|Belize City-Belmopan]]\n| image       =\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| church      = [[Catholic Church]]\n| see         = [[Titular Bishop]] of Thimida Regia\n| appointed   = 18 November 2006\n| term        = 23 January 2007 \u201326  January 2017\n| predecessor = [[Osmond P. Martin]]\n| successor   = \n<!--   Orders   -->\n| ordination     = 27 June 1975\n| ordained_by    = \n| consecration   = 4 April 2002\n| consecrated_by = Bishop [[Osmond P. Martin]]\n| rank           = Auxiliary Bishop of Belize\n<!--   Personal details   -->\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1945|11|15}}\n| birth_place   = [[Belize City]], [[British Honduras]] (now [[Belize]])\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|2020|4|15|1945|11|15|mf=yes|}}<ref name=breakingbelizenews.com>{{cite web| title =Bishop Dorick Wright passes at age 74|url =https://www.breakingbelizenews.com/2020/04/15/bishop-dorrick-wright-passes-at-age-74/|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n| death_place   = \n| previous_post = }}\n\n'''Dorick McGowan Wright, DD,''' (November 15, 1945 \u2013 April 15, 2020) was a [[Belize]]an prelate. From 2006-2017, he has served as the fourth [[Catholic bishop|bishop]] of the [[Catholic Church]] for the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Belize City-Belmopan]].<ref name=Wright>{{cite web| title =Dorick Wright| url =http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bmcgw.html|accessdate=June 19, 2015}}</ref> Pope Francis accepted his resignation on 26 January 2017 and appointed Fr. {{interlanguage link|Lawrence Sydney Nicasio|de}} as the new Bishop.\n\n==Early life==\n\nWright grew up in [[Holy Redeemer Cathedral]] parish in what was then [[British Honduras]]. His first cousin was [[Anglican church|Anglican]] bishop [[Philip S. Wright|Philip Wright]] and his uncle was Pastor Lloyd Wright from Bethel [[Assemblies of God|Assembly of God]] Church.<ref>{{cite web| title =LLoyd Wright| url =http://www.anglicannews.org/news/2005/10/new-bishop-for-the-diocese-of-belize.aspx|accessdate=June 19, 2015}}</ref> In 1961, while in his mid-teens, he lost his mother, two sisters, and a brother in [[hurricane Hattie]]. The tree image on Bishop Wright\u2019s coat of arms is symbolic of the mango tree that saved his life. He attended [[St. John's College, Belize|St. John\u2019s College]] and then taught for three years at [[Holy Redeemer Primary School]]. He then entered [[Conception Abbey|Conception Seminary]], run by the [[Order of St. Benedict]] in north-west [[Missouri]], where he completed his education for the priesthood.<ref name=woods>Woods, Charles M. Sr., et al. ''Years of Grace: The History of Roman Catholic Evangelization in Belize: 1524-2014.'' (Belize: Roman Catholic Diocese of Belize City-Belmopan, 2015), pp. 305f.</ref>\n\n==Episcopacy==\n\nWright was ordained at [[Holy Redeemer Cathedral]], Belize City, on June 27, 1975. He then assisted at St. Joseph Parish, [[Holy Redeemer Catholic Parish, Belize City|Holy Redeemer Cathedral parish]], and Inmaculada Parish in Orange Walk. He returned to St. Joseph Parish as pastor and then to Holy Redeemer Cathedral. On April 4, 2002, Wright was consecrated at St. John\u2019s College as [[Auxiliary bishop|Auxiliary]] to Bishop [[Osmond P. Martin]], with Martin the principal consecrator. He was appointed bishop of the diocese on November 18, 2006, and installed on January 23, 2007, with Archbishop [[Luigi Pezzuto]], [[nuncio]] for Belize and [[El Salvador]], presiding.<ref name=woods/>\n\nBishop Wright founded St. Benedict Diocesan Seminary, a minor seminary offering two years of college training to those studying for the priesthood. It opened on August 27, 2013, on the grounds of the former Santa Familia [[Benedictine]] Monastery outside [[San Ignacio, Belize|Santa Elena]], Belize. Four young men comprised its first class.<ref>{{cite web| title =Seminary| url =http://catholic.bz/v1/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=129:new-diocesan-seminary&catid=1:latest-news&Itemid=18| accessdate =June 19, 2015| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20150427111333/http://catholic.bz/v1/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=129:new-diocesan-seminary&catid=1:latest-news&Itemid=18| archive-date =April 27, 2015| url-status =dead}}</ref>\n\nWright outspokenly opposed some aspects of the government\u2019s 2013 promotion of [[sexual orientation|same-sex-orientation]] rights. His position was supported by the Belize Evangelical Council, and later also by the Belize Council of Churches that included the [[Roman Catholic Church in Belize]] as a member.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.refworld.org/pdfid/50af2ee72.pdf|title=Country-of-origin information to support the adjudication of asylum claims from Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender and Intersex (\u2018LGBTI\u2019) asylum-seekers|last=|first=|date=November 14, 2012|website=Asylum Research Consultancy|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> With Bishop Wright\u2019s eyesight failing, he requested help to carry out his mission and in 2012 [[Viatorian]] Fr. [[Christopher Glancy]] was consecrated Auxiliary Bishop and [[Vicar General]] for the Diocese of Belize City-Belmopan.<ref name=Wright/>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wright, Dorick}}\n[[Category:Roman Catholic bishops in Belize]]\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Roman Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:Belizean clergy]]\n[[Category:Belizean Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:People from Belize City]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "All Hallow's Wraith", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dorick_M._Wright"}
{"title_page": "Asian water monitor", "text_new": "{{redirect|Water monitor}}\n{{redirect-distinguish|Varanus salvator|Varanus salvadorii}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Asian water monitor\n| image = Varanus salvator - 01.jpg\n| image_upright = 1.2\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{Cite iucn | author = Bennett, D. | author2 = Gaulke, M. | author3 = Pianka, E. R. | author4 = Somaweera, R. | author5 = Sweet, S. S. | last-author-amp = yes | title = ''Varanus salvator'' | volume = 2010 | page = e.T178214A7499172 | date = 2010 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2010-4.RLTS.T178214A7499172.en | accessdate = 22 December 2019}}</ref>\n| genus = Varanus\n| species = salvator\n| authority = ([[Josephus Nicolaus Laurenti|Laurenti]], 1768)\n}}\n\nThe '''Asian water monitor''' (''Varanus salvator''), also called '''common water monitor''', is a large [[varanid]] lizard native to [[South Asia|South]] and [[Southeast Asia]]. It is one of the most common monitor lizards in [[Asia]], ranging from [[Sri Lanka]] and coastal northeast [[India]] to [[Indochina]], [[Malay Peninsula]], and [[Indonesia]]n islands where it lives close to water. It is listed as [[Least Concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]].<ref name=IUCN /> It was [[Scientific description|described]] by Laurenti in 1768 and is among the largest [[squamate]]s in the world.<ref name=Koch2007>{{Cite journal|last=Koch|first=A.|date=2007|title=Morphological Studies on the Systematics of South East Asian Water Monitors (''Varanus salvator'' Complex): Nominotypic Populations and Taxonomic Overview|url=|journal=Mertensiella|volume=16|issue=109 |page=e80}}</ref>\n\nThe Asian water monitor is also called '''Malayan water monitor''', '''common water monitor''', '''two-banded monitor''', '''rice lizard''', '''ring lizard''', '''plain lizard''' and '''no-mark lizard''', as well as simply '''water monitor'''. The local name in Sri Lanka is '''kabaragoya''', denoting a subspecies with distinct morphological features.<ref name=ria-tan>{{cite web|url=http://www.naturia.per.sg/buloh/verts/monitor_lizard.htm |title=Mangrove and wetland wildlife at Sungei Buloh Wetlands Reserve: Malayan Water Monitor Lizard |publisher=Naturia.per.sg |author=Ria Tan |year=2001 |accessdate=2015-09-15}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\n[[File:Asian Water Monitor, Sri Lanka.jpg|thumb|left|Large ''V. s. salvator'', ~6-7 feet long ([[Ratnapura District|Ratnapura]], Sri Lanka)]]\nThe water monitor is a large species of [[monitor lizard]]. Breeding maturity is attained for males when they are a relatively modest {{convert|40|cm|in|abbr=on}} long and weigh {{convert|1|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, and for females at {{convert|50|cm|in|abbr=on}}. However, they grow much larger throughout life, with males being larger than females.<ref name=\"Shine_1996\">{{cite journal | last = Shine | first = R. |author2=Harlow, P. S. |author3=Keogh, J. S. | title = Commercial harvesting of giant lizards: The biology of water monitors ''Varanus salvator'' in southern Sumatra | journal = Biological Conservation | volume = 77 | issue = 2\u20133 | pages = 125\u2013134 | year = 1996 | doi = 10.1016/0006-3207(96)00008-0 }}</ref> Adults rarely exceed {{convert|1.5|-|2|m|ft|abbr=on}} in length,<ref>Pianka, King & king. Varanoid lizards of the world. 2004</ref> but the largest specimen on record, from Sri Lanka, measured {{convert|3.21|m|ft|abbr=on}}. A common mature weight of ''V. salvator'' can be {{convert|19.5|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Shine_1996\"/><ref>[http://www.wildlife.gov.my/index.php/en/media-centre/archives/202-biawak-air-varanus-salvator-di-rumah-pak-lah Water Monitor Lizard (Varanus salvator) at Pak Lah\u2019s House | Mutakhir]. Wildlife.gov.my (2012-02-23). Retrieved on 2012-08-22.</ref> However, 80 males killed for the leather trade in [[Sumatra]] averaged only {{convert|3.42|kg|lb|abbr=on}} and {{convert|56.6|cm|in|abbr=on}} snout-to-vent and {{convert|142|cm|in|abbr=on}} in total length; 42 females averaged only {{convert|3.52|kg|lb|abbr=on}} and {{convert|59|cm|in|abbr=on}} snout-to-vent and {{convert|149.6|cm|in|abbr=on}} in total length,<ref name=\"Shine_1996\"/> although unskinned outsized specimens weighed {{convert|16|to|20|kg|lb|abbr=on}}. Another study from the same area by the same authors similarly estimated mean body mass for mature specimens at {{convert|20|kg|lb|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Shine |first1=R. |last2=Harlow |first2=P. S. |year=1998 |title=Ecological traits of commercially harvested water monitors, ''Varanus salvator'', in northern Sumatra |journal=Wildlife Research |volume=25 |issue=4 |pages=437\u2212447 |doi= 10.1071/WR97118|url=}}</ref> while yet another study found a series of adults to weigh {{convert|7.6|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"DrydenGreen1992\">{{cite journal|last1=Dryden |first1=G. L. |last2=Green|first2=B. |last3=Wikramanayake |first3=E. D. |last4=Dryden |first4=K. G. |title=Energy and water turnover in two tropical varanid lizards, ''Varanus bengalensis'' and ''V. salvator'' |journal=Copeia |volume=1992 |issue=1 |date=1992 |pages=102\u2013107 |doi=10.2307/1446540|jstor=1446540 }}</ref> The maximum weight of the species is over {{convert|50|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref>[http://www.waza.org/en/zoo/choose-a-species/reptiles/lizards-and-tuatara/varanus-salvator Water Monitor \u2013 Varanus salvator : WAZA : World Association of Zoos and Aquariums]. WAZA. Retrieved on 2012-08-22.</ref> In exceptional cases, the species has been reported to reach {{convert|75|to|90|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, though most such reports are unverified and may be unreliable. They are the world's second-heaviest lizard, after the [[Komodo dragon]].<ref name=\"Shine_1996\"/> Their bodies are muscular, with long, powerful, laterally compressed tails. The scales in this species are keeled; scales found on top of the head have been noted to be  larger than those located on the back. Water monitors are often defined by their dark brown or blackish coloration with yellow spots found on their underside- these yellow markings have a tendency to disappear gradually with age. This species is also denoted by the blackish band with yellow edges extending back from each eye. These monitors have very long necks and an elongated snout. They use their powerful jaws, serrated teeth and sharp claws for both predation and defense. In captivity, Asian water monitors' life expectancy has been determined to be anywhere between 11\u201325 years depending on conditions, in the wild it is considerably shorter.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://wildlife-facts.weebly.com/asian-water-monitor.html|title=Asian Water Monitor|website=Wildlife Facts|access-date=2017-12-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vitalexotics.com/water-monitor-black-dragon-care-sheet/|title=Water Monitor Care Sheet {{!}} Black Dragon Care Sheet {{!}} Varanus salvator Care Sheet {{!}} Vital Exotics|website=www.vitalexotics.com|language=en|access-date=2017-12-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202203120/http://www.vitalexotics.com/water-monitor-black-dragon-care-sheet/|archive-date=2017-12-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat ==\n[[File:Water monitor showing split tongue .jpg|thumb|Showing its split tongue]]\nThe Asian water monitor is widely distributed from India, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, Myanmar and Thailand, Cambodia, Laos, Vietnam, the Chinese [[Guangxi]] and [[Hainan]] provinces, Malaysia, Singapore to the [[Sunda islands]] [[Sumatra]], [[Java]], [[Bali]], [[Borneo]] and [[Sulawesi]]. It inhabits primarily lowland freshwater and brackish [[wetland]]s. It has been recorded up to an altitude of {{convert|1800|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=IUCN/>\n\nAsian water monitors are [[List of semiaquatic tetrapods|semiaquatic]] and opportunistic; they inhabit a variety of natural habitats though predominantly this species resides in primary forests and mangrove swamps. It has been noted that these monitors are not deterred from living in areas of human disturbance. In fact, they have been known to adapt and thrive in agricultural areas as well as cities with canal systems (such as in Sri Lanka, where they are not hunted or persecuted by humans). This species does not thrive in habitats with extensive loss of natural vegetation and aquatic resources. Habitats that are considered to be most important to this species are mangrove vegetation, swamps, wetlands, and altitudes below 1000 meters.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Behaviour and ecology ==\n[[File:Varanus salvator (illustration).jpg|thumb|Water monitors robbing eggs from a nest. Illustration by [[Pierre Jacques Smit]] from [[Richard Lydekker]]'s ''The Royal Natural History'', 1893\u20131896]]\n[[File:Sri-Lanka water monitor.jpg|thumb|''V. s. salvator'' with full belly at Kandy Lake, Sri Lanka. Possibly obese or gravid, maybe both.]]\nWater monitors defend themselves using their tails, claws, and jaws. They are excellent swimmers, using the raised fin on their tails to steer through water. They are carnivores, and consume a wide range of prey. They are known to eat [[fish]], [[frog]]s, [[rodent]]s, [[bird]]s, [[crab]]s, and [[snake]]s.<ref name=\"Sprackland\"/> They have also been known to eat [[turtle]]s, as well as young [[crocodile]]s and crocodile eggs.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Whitaker | first1 = R. | year = 1981 | title = Bangladesh \u2013 Monitors and turtles | url = | journal = Hamadryad | volume = 6 | issue = 3| pages = 7\u20139}}</ref> Water monitors have been observed eating [[catfish]] in a fashion similar to a mammalian carnivore, tearing off chunks of meat with their sharp teeth while holding it with their front legs and then separating different parts of the fish for sequential consumption.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://varanidae.org/4-4_Stanner.pdf |journal=Biawak |volume=4 |issue=4 |pages=128\u2013131 |year=2010 |title=Mammal-like Feeding Behavior of ''Varanus salvator'' and its Conservational Implications |author=Stanner, M.}}</ref>\n\nIn dominantly aquatic habitats their semiaquatic behavior is considered to provide a measure of safety from predators. Paired with their generalist diet, this is thought to contribute to their ecological plasticity.<ref name=\":2\" /> When hunted by predators such as the [[king cobra]] (''Ophiophagus hannah'') they will climb trees using their powerful legs and claws. If this evasion is not enough to escape danger, they have also been known to jump from trees into streams for safety, a tactic similar to that of the [[green iguana]] (''Iguana iguana'').<ref name=\":1\"/>\n\nLike the Komodo dragon, the water monitor will often eat [[carrion]].<ref name=\"Sprackland\"/><ref name=\"Khan2017\">{{cite journal|last1= Rahman|first1=K. M. M.|last2= Rakhimov|first2=I. I.|last3= Khan |first3=M. M. H. |title=Activity budgets and dietary investigations of ''Varanus salvator'' (Reptilia: Varanidae) in Karamjal ecotourism spot of Bangladesh Sundarbans mangrove forest |journal=Basic and Applied Herpetology |year=2017 |volume= 31 |pages= 45\u201356 |doi=10.11160/bah.79}}</ref> They have a keen sense of smell and can smell a carcass from far away. They are known to feed on dead human bodies. While on the one hand their presence can be helpful in locating a missing person in forensic investigations, on the other hand they can inflict further injuries to the corpse, complicating ascertainment of the cause of death.<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Gunethilake, K. M. T. B. and Vidanapathirana, M. | year = 2016 | title = Water monitors; Implications in forensic death investigations | journal = Medico-Legal Journal of Sri Lanka | volume = 4 | issue = 2 |pages = 48\u201352 | doi=10.4038/mljsl.v4i2.7338}}</ref>\n\nThe first description of the water monitor and its behaviour in English literature was made in 1681 by [[Robert Knox (sailor)|Robert Knox]], who observed it during his long confinement in the [[Kingdom of Kandy]]: \u201cThere is a Creature here called Kobberaguion, resembling an Alligator. The biggest may be five or six feet long, speckled black and white. He lives most upon the Land, but will take the water and dive under it: hath a long blue forked tongue like a sting, which he puts forth and hisseth and gapeth, but doth not bite nor sting, tho the appearance of him would scare those that knew not what he was. He is not afraid of people, but will lie gaping and hissing at them in the way, and will scarce stir out of it. He will come and eat Carrion with the Dogs and Jackals, and will not be scared away by them, but if they come near to bark or snap at him, with his tail, which is long like a whip, he will so slash them, that they will run away and howl.\u201d<ref>{{cite book |author=Knox, R. |title=An Historical Relation of the Island of Ceylon in the East Indies: Together With, an Account of the Detaining in Captivity the Author, and Divers, Other Englishmen Now Living There, and of the Author's Miraculous Escape |location=London |year=1681 |publisher=Richard Chiswell}}</ref>\n\nWater monitors should be handled with care since they have many sharp teeth and can give gashing bites that can sever tendons and veins, causing extensive bleeding. The bite of a large pet water monitor was described by its American owner as being worse than that of a rattlesnake.<ref>Durham. Dave. \u201cWorst Monitor Lizard Bite!\u201d. Accessed on 15.8.2017 on https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gmn4GGQaVuc</ref>\n\n===Venom===\nThe possibility of [[venom]] in the genus ''Varanus'' is widely debated. Previously, venom was thought to be unique to [[Serpentes]] (snakes) and ''[[Heloderma]]'' (venomous lizards). The aftereffects of a ''Varanus'' bite were thought to be due to oral [[bacteria]] alone, but recent studies have shown [[venom]] glands are likely to be present in the mouths of several, if not all, of the species. The venom may be used as a defensive mechanism to fend off predators, to help digest food, to sustain oral hygiene, and possibly to help in capturing and killing prey.<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Arbuckle, K. |url=http://www.varanidae.org/Vol3_No2_Arbuckle.pdf |title=Ecological Function of Venom in ''Varanus'', with a Compilation of Dietary Records from the Literature|journal=Biowak |volume=3 |issue=2 |pages=46\u221256 |year=2009}}</ref><ref>Yong, Ed. [http://phenomena.nationalgeographic.com/2013/06/27/the-myth-of-the-komodo-dragons-dirty-mouth/ The Myth of the Komodo Dragon\u2019s Dirty Mouth], ''National Geographic'', 06/27/2013. Accessed 15.8.2017.</ref>  ''Varanus salvator'' has not yet been specifically tested, but its bites are likely to be consistent with the venomous bites from other varanid lizards.{{Citation needed|reason=Original Research?|date=May 2018}}\n\n=== Predation ===\nAdult water monitors have few natural predators, and are only know to be preyed on by [[Saltwater crocodile|saltwater crocodiles]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ng|first=Marcus|date=June 2012|title=Predation of an Adult Malaysian Water monitor\nVaranus salvator macromaculatus by an\nEstuarine Crocodile Crocodylus porosus|url=|journal=Biawak|volume=6(1)|pages=34-38|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Threats ==\n[[File: Vararus salvator - Asian water monitor.webm|thumb|Young ''V. s. macromaculatus''.  Video clip|219x219px]]\nMonitor lizards are traded globally and are the most common type of lizard to be exported from Southeast Asia, with 8.1 million exported between 1998 and 2007.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Nijman |first=V. |year=2010 |title=An overview of international wildlife trade from Southeast Asia |journal=Biodiversity and Conservation |volume=19 |pages=1101\u22121114 |issue=4 |doi=10.1007/s10531-009-9758-4 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/225940648}}</ref> The Asian water monitor is one of the most exploited varanids; its skin is used for fashion accessories such as shoes, belts and handbags which are shipped globally, with as many as 1.5 million skins traded annually.<ref name=IUCN/> Other uses include a perceived remedy for skin ailments and eczema,<ref>{{Cite journal |author=Uyeda, L. |author2=Iskandar, E. |author3=Purbatrapsila, A. |author4=Pamungkas, J. |author5=Wirsing, A. |author6=Kyes, R. |year=2014 |title=Water Monitor Lizard (''Varanus salvator'') Satay: A Treatment for Skin Ailments in Muarabinuangeun and Cisiih, Indonesia |journal=Biawak |volume=8 |issue=1 |pages=35\u201338 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/263374994}}</ref> novelty food in Indonesia,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nijman|first=V. |year=2015 |title=Water Monitor Lizards for Sale as Novelty Food in Java, Indonesia |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/281711482 |journal=Biawak |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=28\u221232}}</ref> and a perceived [[aphrodisiac]],<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nijman |first=V. |year=2016 |title=Perceptions of Sundanese Men Towards the Consumption of Water Monitor Lizard Meat in West Java, Indonesia |journal=Biawak |volume=10 |issue=1 |pages=22\u221225 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/305379229}}</ref> and as pets.<ref name=\"chula\" />\n\n== Conservation ==\nIn [[Nepal]], it is a protected species under the Wild Animals Protection Act of 2002. In [[Hong Kong]], it is a [[List of protected species in Hong Kong|protected species]] under Wild Animals Protection Ordinance Cap 170. In Malaysia, this species is one of the most common wild animals, with numbers comparable to the population of macaques there. Although many fall victim to humans via [[roadkill]] and animal cruelty, they still thrive in most states of Malaysia, especially in the shrubs of the east coast states such as [[Pahang]] and [[Terengganu]]. In Thailand, all monitor lizards are protected species.<ref name=\"chula\">{{cite journal |author1=Komsorn L. |author2=Kumthorn Thirakhupt |lastauthoramp=yes |date=2001 |title=Species Diversity, Distribution and Proposed Status of Monitor Lizards (Family Varanidae) in Southern Thailand |journal=The Natural History Journal of Chulalongkorn University |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=39\u201346 |url=http://www.thaiscience.info/Article%20for%20ThaiScience/Article/5/Ts-5%20species%20diversity,%20distribution%20and%20proposed%20status%20of%20monitor%20lizards%20%28family%20varanidae%29%20in%20southern%20thailand.pdf |accessdate=2015-01-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304123110/http://www.thaiscience.info/Article%20for%20ThaiScience/Article/5/Ts-5%20species%20diversity,%20distribution%20and%20proposed%20status%20of%20monitor%20lizards%20%28family%20varanidae%29%20in%20southern%20thailand.pdf |archive-date=2016-03-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It is still common in large urban areas in Thailand and is frequently seen in Bangkok's canals and parks. Because of this, it is currently listed as Least Concern in the IUCN Red List and in CITES Appendix 2. These classifications have been made on the basis that this species maintains a geographically wide distribution, can be found in a variety of habitats, adapts to habitats disturbed by humans, and is abundant in portions of its range despite large levels of harvesting.<ref name=IUCN />\n\nLoss of habitat and hunting has exterminated water monitors from most of mainland India.  In other areas they survive despite being hunted, due in part to the fact that larger ones, including large females that breed large numbers of eggs, have tough skins that are not desirable.<ref name=\"ria-tan\" />\n  \nIn Sri Lanka, it is protected by local people who value its predation of \"crabs that would otherwise undermine the banks of rice fields\".<ref name=ria-tan/> It is also protected as it eats venomous snakes.<ref>{{cite book |author=Wirz, P. |title=Exorcism and the Art of Healing in Ceylon |location=Leiden |publisher=Brill |year=1954 |page=238}}</ref>\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nAsian water monitors fall within the kingdom: Animalia, phylum: Chorodata, class: Reptilia, order: Squamata, family: Varanidae, genus: ''Varanus'', and species: ''V. salvator''.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/178214/0|title=Varanus salvator (Common Water Monitor)|access-date=2017-12-01}}</ref> The family: Varanidae contains nearly 80 species of monitor lizards, all of which belong to the genus: ''Varanus''. This genus has been proven to show the widest size range of any vertebrate genus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/neuroscience/parietal-eye|title=Parietal eye - an overview {{!}} ScienceDirect Topics|website=www.sciencedirect.com|language=en|access-date=2017-12-01}}</ref> There is a significant amount of taxonomic uncertainty within this species complex. Morphological analyses have begun to unravel this taxonomic uncertainty but molecular studies are needed to test and confirm the validity of this evidence. Research initiatives such as these are very important for changes in conservation assessments.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Subspecies ===\n*[[File:Great big monitor lizard who goes swimming Sri Lanka.jpg|thumb|''V. s. salvator'']]The Asian water monitor, ''V. s. salvator'', the [[nominate subspecies]], is now restricted to [[Sri Lanka]], where it is known as the ''kabaragoya'' (\u0d9a\u0db6\u0dbb\u0d9c\u0ddc\u0dba\u0dcf) in [[Sinhalese language|Sinhala]] and ''kalawathan'' in [[Tamil language|Tamil]].\n*The Andaman Islands water monitor, ''V. s. andamanensis'', is found on the [[Andaman Islands]]; the type locality is Port Blair, Andaman Islands.\n*The two-striped water monitor, ''V. s. bivittatus'', is common to [[Java]], [[Bali]], [[Lombok]], [[Sumbawa]], [[Flores]], Ombai ([[Alor Island|Alor]]), [[Wetar]], and some neighbouring islands within the Sunda arch, Indonesia; the type locality is Java (designated by Mertens 1959).\n*[[File:Monitor lizard - Pulau Sapi - Sabah - Borneo - Malaysia - panoramio.jpg|thumb|Melanistic ''V. s. macromaculatus'']]The black water monitor, ''V. s. komaini'', from [[Thailand]] (type locality: Amphoe La-ngu, Satun Prov., Thailand, and Thai-Malaysian border area), was formerly a subspecies, but now is regarded as a junior synonym and [[melanistic]] population of ''V. s. macromaculatus''.<ref name=Koch2007/> It is known as the \"black dragon\" or \"black water monitor\" (\u0e21\u0e31\u0e07\u0e01\u0e23\u0e14\u0e33, \u0e40\u0e2b\u0e35\u0e49\u0e22\u0e14\u0e33) in [[Thai language|Thai]]<ref>{{cite news|title=\u0e42\u0e0a\u0e27\u0e4c\"\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e35\u0e49\u0e22\u0e14\u0e33\"\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e15\u0e27\u0e4c\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e22\u0e32\u0e01\u0e0a\u0e19\u0e34\u0e14\u0e43\u0e2b\u0e21\u0e48|url=http://tnews.teenee.com/weird/12029.html|work=tnews.teenee|date=June 8, 2007|accessdate=July 28, 2016|language=Thai}}</ref>\n*The Southeast Asian water monitor, ''V. s. macromaculatus'' (type locality: Siam [Thailand]), is found in mainland Southeast Asia, Singapore, Sumatra, Borneo, and smaller associated offshore islands.<ref name=Koch2007/>\n*Ziegler's water monitor, ''V. s. ziegleri'', is from [[Obi Island]].\n*''[[Varanus cumingi]]'', ''[[Varanus marmoratus]]'', and ''[[Varanus nuchalis]]'' were classified as subspecies until 2007, when they were elevated to full species.<ref name=\"Koch2007\" /><ref>{{cite web|work=monitor-lizards.net |title=Soterosaurus: Mindanao Water Monitor |url=http://www.monitor-lizards.net/species/soterosaurus/cumingi.html |accessdate=20 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120731220924/http://www.monitor-lizards.net/species/soterosaurus/cumingi.html |archivedate=31 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\n== Etymology and local names ==\n[[File:The water monitor warning sign.jpg|thumb|Roadway ''Varanus'' crossing sign at [[Thammasat University]], Thailand]]\nThe [[genus|generic]] name ''Varanus'' is derived from the [[Arabic (language)|Arabic]] ''waral'' ({{lang|ar|\u0648\u0631\u0644}}), which translates as \"monitor\". The [[specific name (zoology)|specific name]] is the Latin word for \"saviour\", denoting a possible religious connotation.<ref name=\"Sprackland\">{{cite book |author=Sprackland, R. G. |title=Giant lizards |publisher=T.F.H. Publications |location=Neptune, NJ |year=1992 |pages= |isbn=978-0-86622-634-9}}</ref> The water monitor is occasionally confused with the [[crocodile monitor]] (''V. salvadorii'') because of their similar scientific names.<ref name=\"badger\">{{cite book |author1=Netherton, J. |author2=Badger, D. P. |title=Lizards: A Natural History of Some Uncommon Creatures\u2014Extraordinary Chameleons, Iguanas, Geckos, and More |url=https://archive.org/details/lizards00davi |url-access=registration |publisher=Voyageur Press |location=Stillwater, MN |year=2002 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/lizards00davi/page/140 140\u2013141] |isbn=978-0-7603-2579-7 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nIn Thailand, the local word for a water monitor, ''hia'' ({{lang|th|\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e35\u0e49\u0e22}}), is used as an insulting word for bad and evil things, including bad persons. The word is also thought to bring bad luck, so some people prefer to call the animals 'silver-and-gold' ({{lang|th|\u0e15\u0e31\u0e27\u0e40\u0e07\u0e34\u0e19\u0e15\u0e31\u0e27\u0e17\u0e2d\u0e07}}) to avoid the jinx.{{cn|date=July 2019}}\nThe origin of this offensive meaning can be traced back to a time when more people lived in rural areas in close proximity to monitor lizards.  Traditionally, Thai villagers lived in two-story houses; the top floor was for living, while the ground floor was designed to be a space for domestic animals such as pigs, chickens, and dogs. Water monitors entered the ground floor and eat or maim the domestic animals, also hence the other name ''dtua gin gai'' ({{lang|th|\u0e15\u0e31\u0e27\u0e01\u0e34\u0e19\u0e44\u0e01\u0e48 }} \u2018chicken eater\u2019) or ''nong chorakae'' ({{lang|th|\u0e19\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e08\u0e23\u0e30\u0e40\u0e02\u0e49}} \u2018younger brother of crocodile\u2019, \u2018little crocodile\u2019) and even sometimes called ''ta kuat'' ({{lang|th|\u0e15\u0e30\u0e01\u0e27\u0e14}}), which in fact refers to a [[Bengal monitor]] (''V. bengalensis''), a different species.<ref name=lao>{{cite web |publisher=[[Pantip.com]]|title=\u0e04\u0e33\u0e2b\u0e22\u0e32\u0e1a\u0e04\u0e32\u0e22\u0e02\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e04\u0e19\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22\u0e40\u0e23\u0e34\u0e48\u0e21\u0e21\u0e32\u0e08\u0e32\u0e01\u0e44\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e04\u0e23\u0e31\u0e1a |accessdate=July 28, 2016 |date=2009 |url=http://topicstock.pantip.com/wahkor/topicstock/2009/11/X8498655/X8498655.html |first= |last= |language=Thai}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Bahasa Indonesia]] and [[Malay language]], the Asian water monitor is called ''biawak air''.<ref>{{Cite journal |date=2016 |title=Studi Histokimia Sebaran Karbohidrat Usus Biawak Air (''Varanus salvator'') |journal=Acta Veterinaria Indonesiana |volume=3 |issue=2 |authors=Wahyuni, S., Jalaluddin, M. and Adnyane, I. K .M. |pages=77\u201384 |url=http://jagb.journal.ipb.ac.id/index.php/actavetindones/article/download/11199/8740|doi=10.29244/avi.3.2.77-84 }}</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Bindenwaran-101.jpg|Closeup of the head\nFile:Flickr - don macauley - Varanus salvator.jpg|Split tongue of ''V. s. macromaculatus''\nFile:Water monitor.jpg|''V. s. macromaculatus'' resting on tree limb\nFile:Varan0022.jpg|A hatchling\nFile:Water monitor walking on the ground.jpg|Walking on pavement\nFile:Close up of the head water monitor.jpg|Head closeup\nFile:Water Monitor Sunderban National Park West Bengal India 22.08.2014.jpg|Asian water monitor showing split tongue ([[Sunderbans National Park]], [[West Bengal]], [[India]])\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Das | first1 = Indraneil | year = 1988 | title = New evidence of the occurrence of water monitor (''Varanus salvator'') in Meghalaya | url = | journal = J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc. | volume = 86 | issue = | pages = 253\u2013255 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Deraniyagala | first1 = P. E. P. | year = 1944 | title = Four New Races of the ''Kabaragoya'' Lizard ''Varanus salvator'' | url = | journal = Spolia Zeylanica | volume = 24 | issue = | pages = 59\u201362 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Pandav | first1 = Bivash | year = 1993 | title = A preliminary survey of the water monitor (''Varanus salvator'') in Bhitarkanika Wildlife Sanctuary, Orissa | url = | journal = Hamadryad | volume = 18 | issue = | pages = 49\u201351 }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Varanus salvator|''Varanus salvator''}}\n* [http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/site/accounts/information/Varanus_salvator.html Animal Diversity Web]\n* [http://reptile-database.reptarium.cz/species.php?genus=Varanus&species=salvator JCVI.org]\n* [http://www.reptile-database.org/ The New Reptile Database]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160311111424/http://hygen.net/blog?p=147 Photos \u2013 water monitor swimming]\n\n{{Varanoidea}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q655616}}\n\n[[Category:Monitor lizards]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Brunei]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Cambodia]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of India]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Laos]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Thailand]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Fauna of Borneo]]\n[[Category:Reptiles described in 1768]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Josephus Nicolaus Laurenti]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Water monitor}}\n{{redirect-distinguish|Varanus salvator|Varanus salvadorii}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Asian water monitor\n| image = Varanus salvator - 01.jpg\n| image_upright = 1.2\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{Cite iucn | author = Bennett, D. | author2 = Gaulke, M. | author3 = Pianka, E. R. | author4 = Somaweera, R. | author5 = Sweet, S. S. | last-author-amp = yes | title = ''Varanus salvator'' | volume = 2010 | page = e.T178214A7499172 | date = 2010 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2010-4.RLTS.T178214A7499172.en | accessdate = 22 December 2019}}</ref>\n| genus = Varanus\n| species = salvator\n| authority = ([[Josephus Nicolaus Laurenti|Laurenti]], 1768)\n}}\n\nThe '''Asian water monitor''' (''Varanus salvator''), also called '''common water monitor''', is a large [[varanid]] lizard native to [[South Asia|South]] and [[Southeast Asia]]. It is one of the most common monitor lizards in [[Asia]], ranging from [[Sri Lanka]] and coastal northeast [[India]] to [[Indochina]], [[Malay Peninsula]], and [[Indonesia]]n islands where it lives close to water. It is listed as [[Least Concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]].<ref name=IUCN /> It was [[Scientific description|described]] by Laurenti in 1768 and is among the largest [[squamate]]s in the world.<ref name=Koch2007>{{Cite journal|last=Koch|first=A.|date=2007|title=Morphological Studies on the Systematics of South East Asian Water Monitors (''Varanus salvator'' Complex): Nominotypic Populations and Taxonomic Overview|url=|journal=Mertensiella|volume=16|issue=109 |page=e80}}</ref>\n\nThe Asian water monitor is also called '''Malayan water monitor''', '''common water monitor''', '''two-banded monitor''', '''rice lizard''', '''ring lizard''', '''plain lizard''' and '''no-mark lizard''', as well as simply '''water monitor'''. The local name in Sri Lanka is '''kabaragoya''', denoting a subspecies with distinct morphological features.<ref name=ria-tan>{{cite web|url=http://www.naturia.per.sg/buloh/verts/monitor_lizard.htm |title=Mangrove and wetland wildlife at Sungei Buloh Wetlands Reserve: Malayan Water Monitor Lizard |publisher=Naturia.per.sg |author=Ria Tan |year=2001 |accessdate=2015-09-15}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\n[[File:Asian Water Monitor, Sri Lanka.jpg|thumb|left|Large ''V. s. salvator'', ~6-7 feet long ([[Ratnapura District|Ratnapura]], Sri Lanka)]]\nThe water monitor is a large species of [[monitor lizard]]. Breeding maturity is attained for males when they are a relatively modest {{convert|40|cm|in|abbr=on}} long and weigh {{convert|1|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, and for females at {{convert|50|cm|in|abbr=on}}. However, they grow much larger throughout life, with males being larger than females.<ref name=\"Shine_1996\">{{cite journal | last = Shine | first = R. |author2=Harlow, P. S. |author3=Keogh, J. S. | title = Commercial harvesting of giant lizards: The biology of water monitors ''Varanus salvator'' in southern Sumatra | journal = Biological Conservation | volume = 77 | issue = 2\u20133 | pages = 125\u2013134 | year = 1996 | doi = 10.1016/0006-3207(96)00008-0 }}</ref> Adults rarely exceed {{convert|1.5|-|2|m|ft|abbr=on}} in length,<ref>Pianka, King & king. Varanoid lizards of the world. 2004</ref> but the largest specimen on record, from Sri Lanka, measured {{convert|3.21|m|ft|abbr=on}}. A common mature weight of ''V. salvator'' can be {{convert|19.5|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Shine_1996\"/><ref>[http://www.wildlife.gov.my/index.php/en/media-centre/archives/202-biawak-air-varanus-salvator-di-rumah-pak-lah Water Monitor Lizard (Varanus salvator) at Pak Lah\u2019s House | Mutakhir]. Wildlife.gov.my (2012-02-23). Retrieved on 2012-08-22.</ref> However, 80 males killed for the leather trade in [[Sumatra]] averaged only {{convert|3.42|kg|lb|abbr=on}} and {{convert|56.6|cm|in|abbr=on}} snout-to-vent and {{convert|142|cm|in|abbr=on}} in total length; 42 females averaged only {{convert|3.52|kg|lb|abbr=on}} and {{convert|59|cm|in|abbr=on}} snout-to-vent and {{convert|149.6|cm|in|abbr=on}} in total length,<ref name=\"Shine_1996\"/> although unskinned outsized specimens weighed {{convert|16|to|20|kg|lb|abbr=on}}. Another study from the same area by the same authors similarly estimated mean body mass for mature specimens at {{convert|20|kg|lb|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Shine |first1=R. |last2=Harlow |first2=P. S. |year=1998 |title=Ecological traits of commercially harvested water monitors, ''Varanus salvator'', in northern Sumatra |journal=Wildlife Research |volume=25 |issue=4 |pages=437\u2212447 |doi= 10.1071/WR97118|url=}}</ref> while yet another study found a series of adults to weigh {{convert|7.6|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"DrydenGreen1992\">{{cite journal|last1=Dryden |first1=G. L. |last2=Green|first2=B. |last3=Wikramanayake |first3=E. D. |last4=Dryden |first4=K. G. |title=Energy and water turnover in two tropical varanid lizards, ''Varanus bengalensis'' and ''V. salvator'' |journal=Copeia |volume=1992 |issue=1 |date=1992 |pages=102\u2013107 |doi=10.2307/1446540|jstor=1446540 }}</ref> The maximum weight of the species is over {{convert|50|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref>[http://www.waza.org/en/zoo/choose-a-species/reptiles/lizards-and-tuatara/varanus-salvator Water Monitor \u2013 Varanus salvator : WAZA : World Association of Zoos and Aquariums]. WAZA. Retrieved on 2012-08-22.</ref> In exceptional cases, the species has been reported to reach {{convert|75|to|90|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, though most such reports are unverified and may be unreliable. They are the world's second-heaviest lizard, after the [[Komodo dragon]].<ref name=\"Shine_1996\"/> Their bodies are muscular, with long, powerful, laterally compressed tails. The scales in this species are keeled; scales found on top of the head have been noted to be  larger than those located on the back. Water monitors are often defined by their dark brown or blackish coloration with yellow spots found on their underside- these yellow markings have a tendency to disappear gradually with age. This species is also denoted by the blackish band with yellow edges extending back from each eye. These monitors have very long necks and an elongated snout. They use their powerful jaws, serrated teeth and sharp claws for both predation and defense. In captivity, Asian water monitors' life expectancy has been determined to be anywhere between 11\u201325 years depending on conditions, in the wild it is considerably shorter.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://wildlife-facts.weebly.com/asian-water-monitor.html|title=Asian Water Monitor|website=Wildlife Facts|access-date=2017-12-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vitalexotics.com/water-monitor-black-dragon-care-sheet/|title=Water Monitor Care Sheet {{!}} Black Dragon Care Sheet {{!}} Varanus salvator Care Sheet {{!}} Vital Exotics|website=www.vitalexotics.com|language=en|access-date=2017-12-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202203120/http://www.vitalexotics.com/water-monitor-black-dragon-care-sheet/|archive-date=2017-12-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat ==\n[[File:Water monitor showing split tongue .jpg|thumb|Showing its split tongue]]\nThe Asian water monitor is widely distributed from India, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, Myanmar and Thailand, Cambodia, Laos, Vietnam, the Chinese [[Guangxi]] and [[Hainan]] provinces, Malaysia, Singapore to the [[Sunda islands]] [[Sumatra]], [[Java]], [[Bali]], [[Borneo]] and [[Sulawesi]]. It inhabits primarily lowland freshwater and brackish [[wetland]]s. It has been recorded up to an altitude of {{convert|1800|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=IUCN/>\n\nAsian water monitors are [[List of semiaquatic tetrapods|semiaquatic]] and opportunistic; they inhabit a variety of natural habitats though predominantly this species resides in primary forests and mangrove swamps. It has been noted that these monitors are not deterred from living in areas of human disturbance. In fact, they have been known to adapt and thrive in agricultural areas as well as cities with canal systems (such as in Sri Lanka, where they are not hunted or persecuted by humans). This species does not thrive in habitats with extensive loss of natural vegetation and aquatic resources. Habitats that are considered to be most important to this species are mangrove vegetation, swamps, wetlands, and altitudes below 1000 meters.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Behaviour and ecology ==\n[[File:Varanus salvator (illustration).jpg|thumb|Water monitors robbing eggs from a nest. Illustration by [[Pierre Jacques Smit]] from [[Richard Lydekker]]'s ''The Royal Natural History'', 1893\u20131896]]\n[[File:Sri-Lanka water monitor.jpg|thumb|''V. s. salvator'' with full belly at Kandy Lake, Sri Lanka. Probably obese or gravid, maybe both.]]\nWater monitors defend themselves using their tails, claws, and jaws. They are excellent swimmers, using the raised fin on their tails to steer through water. They are carnivores, and consume a wide range of prey. They are known to eat [[fish]], [[frog]]s, [[rodent]]s, [[bird]]s, [[crab]]s, and [[snake]]s.<ref name=\"Sprackland\"/> They have also been known to eat [[turtle]]s, as well as young [[crocodile]]s and crocodile eggs.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Whitaker | first1 = R. | year = 1981 | title = Bangladesh \u2013 Monitors and turtles | url = | journal = Hamadryad | volume = 6 | issue = 3| pages = 7\u20139}}</ref> Water monitors have been observed eating [[catfish]] in a fashion similar to a mammalian carnivore, tearing off chunks of meat with their sharp teeth while holding it with their front legs and then separating different parts of the fish for sequential consumption.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://varanidae.org/4-4_Stanner.pdf |journal=Biawak |volume=4 |issue=4 |pages=128\u2013131 |year=2010 |title=Mammal-like Feeding Behavior of ''Varanus salvator'' and its Conservational Implications |author=Stanner, M.}}</ref>\n\nIn dominantly aquatic habitats their semiaquatic behavior is considered to provide a measure of safety from predators. Paired with their generalist diet, this is thought to contribute to their ecological plasticity.<ref name=\":2\" /> When hunted by predators such as the [[king cobra]] (''Ophiophagus hannah'') they will climb trees using their powerful legs and claws. If this evasion is not enough to escape danger, they have also been known to jump from trees into streams for safety, a tactic similar to that of the [[green iguana]] (''Iguana iguana'').<ref name=\":1\"/>\n\nLike the Komodo dragon, the water monitor will often eat [[carrion]].<ref name=\"Sprackland\"/><ref name=\"Khan2017\">{{cite journal|last1= Rahman|first1=K. M. M.|last2= Rakhimov|first2=I. I.|last3= Khan |first3=M. M. H. |title=Activity budgets and dietary investigations of ''Varanus salvator'' (Reptilia: Varanidae) in Karamjal ecotourism spot of Bangladesh Sundarbans mangrove forest |journal=Basic and Applied Herpetology |year=2017 |volume= 31 |pages= 45\u201356 |doi=10.11160/bah.79}}</ref> They have a keen sense of smell and can smell a carcass from far away. They are known to feed on dead human bodies. While on the one hand their presence can be helpful in locating a missing person in forensic investigations, on the other hand they can inflict further injuries to the corpse, complicating ascertainment of the cause of death.<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Gunethilake, K. M. T. B. and Vidanapathirana, M. | year = 2016 | title = Water monitors; Implications in forensic death investigations | journal = Medico-Legal Journal of Sri Lanka | volume = 4 | issue = 2 |pages = 48\u201352 | doi=10.4038/mljsl.v4i2.7338}}</ref>\n\nThe first description of the water monitor and its behaviour in English literature was made in 1681 by [[Robert Knox (sailor)|Robert Knox]], who observed it during his long confinement in the [[Kingdom of Kandy]]: \u201cThere is a Creature here called Kobberaguion, resembling an Alligator. The biggest may be five or six feet long, speckled black and white. He lives most upon the Land, but will take the water and dive under it: hath a long blue forked tongue like a sting, which he puts forth and hisseth and gapeth, but doth not bite nor sting, tho the appearance of him would scare those that knew not what he was. He is not afraid of people, but will lie gaping and hissing at them in the way, and will scarce stir out of it. He will come and eat Carrion with the Dogs and Jackals, and will not be scared away by them, but if they come near to bark or snap at him, with his tail, which is long like a whip, he will so slash them, that they will run away and howl.\u201d<ref>{{cite book |author=Knox, R. |title=An Historical Relation of the Island of Ceylon in the East Indies: Together With, an Account of the Detaining in Captivity the Author, and Divers, Other Englishmen Now Living There, and of the Author's Miraculous Escape |location=London |year=1681 |publisher=Richard Chiswell}}</ref>\n\nWater monitors should be handled with care since they have many sharp teeth and can give gashing bites that can sever tendons and veins, causing extensive bleeding. The bite of a large pet water monitor was described by its American owner as being worse than that of a rattlesnake.<ref>Durham. Dave. \u201cWorst Monitor Lizard Bite!\u201d. Accessed on 15.8.2017 on https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gmn4GGQaVuc</ref>\n\n===Venom===\nThe possibility of [[venom]] in the genus ''Varanus'' is widely debated. Previously, venom was thought to be unique to [[Serpentes]] (snakes) and ''[[Heloderma]]'' (venomous lizards). The aftereffects of a ''Varanus'' bite were thought to be due to oral [[bacteria]] alone, but recent studies have shown [[venom]] glands are likely to be present in the mouths of several, if not all, of the species. The venom may be used as a defensive mechanism to fend off predators, to help digest food, to sustain oral hygiene, and possibly to help in capturing and killing prey.<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Arbuckle, K. |url=http://www.varanidae.org/Vol3_No2_Arbuckle.pdf |title=Ecological Function of Venom in ''Varanus'', with a Compilation of Dietary Records from the Literature|journal=Biowak |volume=3 |issue=2 |pages=46\u221256 |year=2009}}</ref><ref>Yong, Ed. [http://phenomena.nationalgeographic.com/2013/06/27/the-myth-of-the-komodo-dragons-dirty-mouth/ The Myth of the Komodo Dragon\u2019s Dirty Mouth], ''National Geographic'', 06/27/2013. Accessed 15.8.2017.</ref>  ''Varanus salvator'' has not yet been specifically tested, but its bites are likely to be consistent with the venomous bites from other varanid lizards.{{Citation needed|reason=Original Research?|date=May 2018}}\n\n=== Predation ===\nAdult water monitors have few natural predators, and are only know to be preyed on by [[Saltwater crocodile|saltwater crocodiles]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ng|first=Marcus|date=June 2012|title=Predation of an Adult Malaysian Water monitor\nVaranus salvator macromaculatus by an\nEstuarine Crocodile Crocodylus porosus|url=|journal=Biawak|volume=6(1)|pages=34-38|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Threats ==\n[[File: Vararus salvator - Asian water monitor.webm|thumb|Young ''V. s. macromaculatus''.  Video clip|219x219px]]\nMonitor lizards are traded globally and are the most common type of lizard to be exported from Southeast Asia, with 8.1 million exported between 1998 and 2007.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Nijman |first=V. |year=2010 |title=An overview of international wildlife trade from Southeast Asia |journal=Biodiversity and Conservation |volume=19 |pages=1101\u22121114 |issue=4 |doi=10.1007/s10531-009-9758-4 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/225940648}}</ref> The Asian water monitor is one of the most exploited varanids; its skin is used for fashion accessories such as shoes, belts and handbags which are shipped globally, with as many as 1.5 million skins traded annually.<ref name=IUCN/> Other uses include a perceived remedy for skin ailments and eczema,<ref>{{Cite journal |author=Uyeda, L. |author2=Iskandar, E. |author3=Purbatrapsila, A. |author4=Pamungkas, J. |author5=Wirsing, A. |author6=Kyes, R. |year=2014 |title=Water Monitor Lizard (''Varanus salvator'') Satay: A Treatment for Skin Ailments in Muarabinuangeun and Cisiih, Indonesia |journal=Biawak |volume=8 |issue=1 |pages=35\u201338 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/263374994}}</ref> novelty food in Indonesia,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nijman|first=V. |year=2015 |title=Water Monitor Lizards for Sale as Novelty Food in Java, Indonesia |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/281711482 |journal=Biawak |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=28\u221232}}</ref> and a perceived [[aphrodisiac]],<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nijman |first=V. |year=2016 |title=Perceptions of Sundanese Men Towards the Consumption of Water Monitor Lizard Meat in West Java, Indonesia |journal=Biawak |volume=10 |issue=1 |pages=22\u221225 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/305379229}}</ref> and as pets.<ref name=\"chula\" />\n\n== Conservation ==\nIn [[Nepal]], it is a protected species under the Wild Animals Protection Act of 2002. In [[Hong Kong]], it is a [[List of protected species in Hong Kong|protected species]] under Wild Animals Protection Ordinance Cap 170. In Malaysia, this species is one of the most common wild animals, with numbers comparable to the population of macaques there. Although many fall victim to humans via [[roadkill]] and animal cruelty, they still thrive in most states of Malaysia, especially in the shrubs of the east coast states such as [[Pahang]] and [[Terengganu]]. In Thailand, all monitor lizards are protected species.<ref name=\"chula\">{{cite journal |author1=Komsorn L. |author2=Kumthorn Thirakhupt |lastauthoramp=yes |date=2001 |title=Species Diversity, Distribution and Proposed Status of Monitor Lizards (Family Varanidae) in Southern Thailand |journal=The Natural History Journal of Chulalongkorn University |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=39\u201346 |url=http://www.thaiscience.info/Article%20for%20ThaiScience/Article/5/Ts-5%20species%20diversity,%20distribution%20and%20proposed%20status%20of%20monitor%20lizards%20%28family%20varanidae%29%20in%20southern%20thailand.pdf |accessdate=2015-01-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304123110/http://www.thaiscience.info/Article%20for%20ThaiScience/Article/5/Ts-5%20species%20diversity,%20distribution%20and%20proposed%20status%20of%20monitor%20lizards%20%28family%20varanidae%29%20in%20southern%20thailand.pdf |archive-date=2016-03-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It is still common in large urban areas in Thailand and is frequently seen in Bangkok's canals and parks. Because of this, it is currently listed as Least Concern in the IUCN Red List and in CITES Appendix 2. These classifications have been made on the basis that this species maintains a geographically wide distribution, can be found in a variety of habitats, adapts to habitats disturbed by humans, and is abundant in portions of its range despite large levels of harvesting.<ref name=IUCN />\n\nLoss of habitat and hunting has exterminated water monitors from most of mainland India.  In other areas they survive despite being hunted, due in part to the fact that larger ones, including large females that breed large numbers of eggs, have tough skins that are not desirable.<ref name=\"ria-tan\" />\n  \nIn Sri Lanka, it is protected by local people who value its predation of \"crabs that would otherwise undermine the banks of rice fields\".<ref name=ria-tan/> It is also protected as it eats venomous snakes.<ref>{{cite book |author=Wirz, P. |title=Exorcism and the Art of Healing in Ceylon |location=Leiden |publisher=Brill |year=1954 |page=238}}</ref>\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nAsian water monitors fall within the kingdom: Animalia, phylum: Chorodata, class: Reptilia, order: Squamata, family: Varanidae, genus: ''Varanus'', and species: ''V. salvator''.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/178214/0|title=Varanus salvator (Common Water Monitor)|access-date=2017-12-01}}</ref> The family: Varanidae contains nearly 80 species of monitor lizards, all of which belong to the genus: ''Varanus''. This genus has been proven to show the widest size range of any vertebrate genus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/neuroscience/parietal-eye|title=Parietal eye - an overview {{!}} ScienceDirect Topics|website=www.sciencedirect.com|language=en|access-date=2017-12-01}}</ref> There is a significant amount of taxonomic uncertainty within this species complex. Morphological analyses have begun to unravel this taxonomic uncertainty but molecular studies are needed to test and confirm the validity of this evidence. Research initiatives such as these are very important for changes in conservation assessments.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Subspecies ===\n*[[File:Great big monitor lizard who goes swimming Sri Lanka.jpg|thumb|''V. s. salvator'']]The Asian water monitor, ''V. s. salvator'', the [[nominate subspecies]], is now restricted to [[Sri Lanka]], where it is known as the ''kabaragoya'' (\u0d9a\u0db6\u0dbb\u0d9c\u0ddc\u0dba\u0dcf) in [[Sinhalese language|Sinhala]] and ''kalawathan'' in [[Tamil language|Tamil]].\n*The Andaman Islands water monitor, ''V. s. andamanensis'', is found on the [[Andaman Islands]]; the type locality is Port Blair, Andaman Islands.\n*The two-striped water monitor, ''V. s. bivittatus'', is common to [[Java]], [[Bali]], [[Lombok]], [[Sumbawa]], [[Flores]], Ombai ([[Alor Island|Alor]]), [[Wetar]], and some neighbouring islands within the Sunda arch, Indonesia; the type locality is Java (designated by Mertens 1959).\n*[[File:Monitor lizard - Pulau Sapi - Sabah - Borneo - Malaysia - panoramio.jpg|thumb|Melanistic ''V. s. macromaculatus'']]The black water monitor, ''V. s. komaini'', from [[Thailand]] (type locality: Amphoe La-ngu, Satun Prov., Thailand, and Thai-Malaysian border area), was formerly a subspecies, but now is regarded as a junior synonym and [[melanistic]] population of ''V. s. macromaculatus''.<ref name=Koch2007/> It is known as the \"black dragon\" or \"black water monitor\" (\u0e21\u0e31\u0e07\u0e01\u0e23\u0e14\u0e33, \u0e40\u0e2b\u0e35\u0e49\u0e22\u0e14\u0e33) in [[Thai language|Thai]]<ref>{{cite news|title=\u0e42\u0e0a\u0e27\u0e4c\"\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e35\u0e49\u0e22\u0e14\u0e33\"\u0e2a\u0e31\u0e15\u0e27\u0e4c\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e22\u0e32\u0e01\u0e0a\u0e19\u0e34\u0e14\u0e43\u0e2b\u0e21\u0e48|url=http://tnews.teenee.com/weird/12029.html|work=tnews.teenee|date=June 8, 2007|accessdate=July 28, 2016|language=Thai}}</ref>\n*The Southeast Asian water monitor, ''V. s. macromaculatus'' (type locality: Siam [Thailand]), is found in mainland Southeast Asia, Singapore, Sumatra, Borneo, and smaller associated offshore islands.<ref name=Koch2007/>\n*Ziegler's water monitor, ''V. s. ziegleri'', is from [[Obi Island]].\n*''[[Varanus cumingi]]'', ''[[Varanus marmoratus]]'', and ''[[Varanus nuchalis]]'' were classified as subspecies until 2007, when they were elevated to full species.<ref name=\"Koch2007\" /><ref>{{cite web|work=monitor-lizards.net |title=Soterosaurus: Mindanao Water Monitor |url=http://www.monitor-lizards.net/species/soterosaurus/cumingi.html |accessdate=20 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120731220924/http://www.monitor-lizards.net/species/soterosaurus/cumingi.html |archivedate=31 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\n== Etymology and local names ==\n[[File:The water monitor warning sign.jpg|thumb|Roadway ''Varanus'' crossing sign at [[Thammasat University]], Thailand]]\nThe [[genus|generic]] name ''Varanus'' is derived from the [[Arabic (language)|Arabic]] ''waral'' ({{lang|ar|\u0648\u0631\u0644}}), which translates as \"monitor\". The [[specific name (zoology)|specific name]] is the Latin word for \"saviour\", denoting a possible religious connotation.<ref name=\"Sprackland\">{{cite book |author=Sprackland, R. G. |title=Giant lizards |publisher=T.F.H. Publications |location=Neptune, NJ |year=1992 |pages= |isbn=978-0-86622-634-9}}</ref> The water monitor is occasionally confused with the [[crocodile monitor]] (''V. salvadorii'') because of their similar scientific names.<ref name=\"badger\">{{cite book |author1=Netherton, J. |author2=Badger, D. P. |title=Lizards: A Natural History of Some Uncommon Creatures\u2014Extraordinary Chameleons, Iguanas, Geckos, and More |url=https://archive.org/details/lizards00davi |url-access=registration |publisher=Voyageur Press |location=Stillwater, MN |year=2002 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/lizards00davi/page/140 140\u2013141] |isbn=978-0-7603-2579-7 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nIn Thailand, the local word for a water monitor, ''hia'' ({{lang|th|\u0e40\u0e2b\u0e35\u0e49\u0e22}}), is used as an insulting word for bad and evil things, including bad persons. The word is also thought to bring bad luck, so some people prefer to call the animals 'silver-and-gold' ({{lang|th|\u0e15\u0e31\u0e27\u0e40\u0e07\u0e34\u0e19\u0e15\u0e31\u0e27\u0e17\u0e2d\u0e07}}) to avoid the jinx.{{cn|date=July 2019}}\nThe origin of this offensive meaning can be traced back to a time when more people lived in rural areas in close proximity to monitor lizards.  Traditionally, Thai villagers lived in two-story houses; the top floor was for living, while the ground floor was designed to be a space for domestic animals such as pigs, chickens, and dogs. Water monitors entered the ground floor and eat or maim the domestic animals, also hence the other name ''dtua gin gai'' ({{lang|th|\u0e15\u0e31\u0e27\u0e01\u0e34\u0e19\u0e44\u0e01\u0e48 }} \u2018chicken eater\u2019) or ''nong chorakae'' ({{lang|th|\u0e19\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e08\u0e23\u0e30\u0e40\u0e02\u0e49}} \u2018younger brother of crocodile\u2019, \u2018little crocodile\u2019) and even sometimes called ''ta kuat'' ({{lang|th|\u0e15\u0e30\u0e01\u0e27\u0e14}}), which in fact refers to a [[Bengal monitor]] (''V. bengalensis''), a different species.<ref name=lao>{{cite web |publisher=[[Pantip.com]]|title=\u0e04\u0e33\u0e2b\u0e22\u0e32\u0e1a\u0e04\u0e32\u0e22\u0e02\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e04\u0e19\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22\u0e40\u0e23\u0e34\u0e48\u0e21\u0e21\u0e32\u0e08\u0e32\u0e01\u0e44\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e04\u0e23\u0e31\u0e1a |accessdate=July 28, 2016 |date=2009 |url=http://topicstock.pantip.com/wahkor/topicstock/2009/11/X8498655/X8498655.html |first= |last= |language=Thai}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Bahasa Indonesia]] and [[Malay language]], the Asian water monitor is called ''biawak air''.<ref>{{Cite journal |date=2016 |title=Studi Histokimia Sebaran Karbohidrat Usus Biawak Air (''Varanus salvator'') |journal=Acta Veterinaria Indonesiana |volume=3 |issue=2 |authors=Wahyuni, S., Jalaluddin, M. and Adnyane, I. K .M. |pages=77\u201384 |url=http://jagb.journal.ipb.ac.id/index.php/actavetindones/article/download/11199/8740|doi=10.29244/avi.3.2.77-84 }}</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Bindenwaran-101.jpg|Closeup of the head\nFile:Flickr - don macauley - Varanus salvator.jpg|Split tongue of ''V. s. macromaculatus''\nFile:Water monitor.jpg|''V. s. macromaculatus'' resting on tree limb\nFile:Varan0022.jpg|A hatchling\nFile:Water monitor walking on the ground.jpg|Walking on pavement\nFile:Close up of the head water monitor.jpg|Head closeup\nFile:Water Monitor Sunderban National Park West Bengal India 22.08.2014.jpg|Asian water monitor showing split tongue ([[Sunderbans National Park]], [[West Bengal]], [[India]])\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Das | first1 = Indraneil | year = 1988 | title = New evidence of the occurrence of water monitor (''Varanus salvator'') in Meghalaya | url = | journal = J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc. | volume = 86 | issue = | pages = 253\u2013255 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Deraniyagala | first1 = P. E. P. | year = 1944 | title = Four New Races of the ''Kabaragoya'' Lizard ''Varanus salvator'' | url = | journal = Spolia Zeylanica | volume = 24 | issue = | pages = 59\u201362 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Pandav | first1 = Bivash | year = 1993 | title = A preliminary survey of the water monitor (''Varanus salvator'') in Bhitarkanika Wildlife Sanctuary, Orissa | url = | journal = Hamadryad | volume = 18 | issue = | pages = 49\u201351 }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Varanus salvator|''Varanus salvator''}}\n* [http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/site/accounts/information/Varanus_salvator.html Animal Diversity Web]\n* [http://reptile-database.reptarium.cz/species.php?genus=Varanus&species=salvator JCVI.org]\n* [http://www.reptile-database.org/ The New Reptile Database]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160311111424/http://hygen.net/blog?p=147 Photos \u2013 water monitor swimming]\n\n{{Varanoidea}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q655616}}\n\n[[Category:Monitor lizards]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Brunei]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Cambodia]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of India]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Laos]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Thailand]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Fauna of Borneo]]\n[[Category:Reptiles described in 1768]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Josephus Nicolaus Laurenti]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "name_user": "Bloopityboop", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asian_water_monitor"}
{"title_page": "Nail disease", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Onychia|the squid genus|Onykia|the genus of moth|Onychia (moth)}}\n{{Refimprove|date=March 2008}}\n{{Infobox medical condition (new) \n| name            = Nail disease or disorder \n| image           = ONYCHIA1.JPG \n| caption         = Onychia without [[granuloma]] \n| \n| pronounce       =  \n| field           =  \n| synonyms        =  \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\nA '''nail disease''' or '''onychosis''' is a disease or deformity of the [[nail (anatomy)|nail]].  Although the nail is a structure produced by the skin and is a [[skin appendage]], nail diseases have a distinct classification as they have their own signs and symptoms which may relate to other medical conditions. Some nail conditions that show signs of [[infection]] or [[inflammation]] may require medical assistance.\n\n==Diseases==\n[[File:Human nail anatomy.jpg|thumb|Anatomy of the basic parts of a human [[nail (anatomy)|nail]]. A. Nail plate; B. lunula; C. root; D. sinus; E. matrix; F. [[nail bed (anatomy)|nail bed]]; G. [[eponychium]]; H. free margin.]]\n\n*''Onychia'' is an [[inflammation]] of the nail folds (surrounding tissue of the nail plate) of the nail with formation of [[pus]] and shedding of the nail.  Onychia results from the introduction of microscopic [[pathogen]]s through small wounds.\n*''[[Ingrown nail|Onychocryptosis]]'', commonly known as \"ingrown nails\" (''unguis incarnatus''), can affect either the fingers or the toes.  In this condition, the nail cuts into one or both sides of the [[nail (anatomy)#nail bed|nail bed]], resulting in [[inflammation]] and possibly [[infection]]. The relative rarity of this condition in the fingers suggests that [[pressure]] from the ground or shoe against the toe is a prime factor. The movements involved in [[walking]] or other physical disturbances can contribute to the problem.  Mild [[onychocryptosis]], particularly in the absence of infection, can be treated by trimming and rounding the nail.  More advanced cases, which usually include [[infection]], are treated by [[surgically]] excising the ingrowing portion of the nail down to its bony origin and [[thermally]] or [[chemically]] [[cauterizing]] the matrix, or 'root', to prevent recurrence.  This surgery is called [[matrixectomy]]. The best results are achieved by cauterizing the matrix with [[phenol]]. The [[Ingrown nail|Vandenbos Procedure]] is a highly effective method that focuses on excision of excessive nail fold tissue without affecting the healthy nail and nail matrix. The Vandenbos procedure is showing high success rates in eliminating Onychocryptosis without altering the normal nail. Another, much less effective, treatment is [[Surgery#excision|excision]] of the matrix, sometimes called a 'cold steel procedure'.\n[[File:Ingrown_nail_in_hallux_toe.jpg|thumb|[[Ingrown nail]] in [[hallux]] toe]]\n*''[[Onychodystrophy]]'' is a [[deformity|deformation]] of the nails that can result from cancer [[chemotherapy]] which includes [[bleomycin]], [[hydroxyurea]], or [[5-fluorouracil]]. It can include [[discoloration]] of the nail, or [[dyschromia]].\n*''[[Onychogryposis]]'', also called \"ram's-horn nail\", is a thickening and increase in [[curvature]] of the nail.  It is usually the result of injury to the matrix.  It may be partially [[hereditary]] and can also occur as a result of long-term neglect.  It is most commonly seen in the great [[toe]] but may be seen in other toes as well as the fingernails.  An affected nail has many grooves and ridges, is brownish in color, and grows more quickly on one side than on the other.  The thick curved nail is difficult to cut, and often remains untrimmed, exacerbating the problem.\n[[File:Onychomycosis.JPG|thumb|200px|[[Onychomycosis]] in every nail of the right foot.]]\n\n*''[[Onycholysis]]'' is a loosening of the exposed portion of the nail from the nail bed, usually beginning at the free edge and continuing to the [[lunula (anatomy)|lunula]].  It is frequently associated with an [[internal disorder]], [[Physical trauma|trauma]], [[infection]], [[nail fungi]], [[allergy]] to [[nail enhancement product]]s, or side effects of [[drug]]s.\n*''[[Onychomadesis]]'' is the separation and falling off of a nail from the [[nail (anatomy)#nail bed|nail bed]]. Common causes include localized [[infection]], minor injury to the [[matrix bed]], or severe [[systemic illness]]. It is sometimes a side effect of [[chemotherapy]] or [[x-ray]] treatments for [[cancer]]. A new nail plate will form once the cause of the disease is removed.\n*''[[Onychomycosis]]'', also known as [[tinea|''tinea unguium'']], is a contagious [[infection]] of the nail caused by the same [[fungal organism]]s which cause [[ringworm]] of the [[skin]] (''Trichophyton rubrum'' or ''T. mentagrophytes'', rarely other [[trichophyton]] species or ''Epidermophyton floccosum'' <ref name=\"mycology\">{{cite book |last= Hall |first= John C. |editor= John C. Hall |title= Sauer's Manual of Skin Diseases |edition= 9th |year= 2006 |publisher= Lippincott Williams & Wilkins |location= Philadelphia |isbn= 0-7817-2947-5|pages= 244=266 |chapter= 25. Dermatologic mycology.}}</ref>). It can result in [[discoloration]], [[thickening]], [[chalkiness]], or crumbling of the nails and is often treated by powerful oral medications which, rarely, can cause severe side effects including [[liver failure]]. Mild [[onychomycosis]] sometimes responds to a combination of [[topical]] [[antifungal medication]], sometimes applied as special [[medicinal]] nail [[lacquer]], and [[periodic filing]] of the nail surface. For advanced onychomycosis, especially if more than one nail is [[infection|infected]], systemic medication (pills) is preferred. Home remedies are often used, although their effectiveness is disputed.\n[[Image:HEMORRHAGESUBUNG1.JPG|thumb|right|[[Subungual hematoma]] (mild)]]\n*''[[Onychophosis]]'' is a growth of [[horn (anatomy)|horny]] [[epithelium]] in the nail.\n*''[[Onychoptosis]]'' is the periodic shedding of one or more nails, in whole or part. This condition may follow certain diseases such as [[syphilis]], or can result from [[fever]], trauma, [[systemic upset]]s or [[adverse reaction]] to drugs.\n*''[[Onychorrhexis]]'' also known as brittle nails, is brittleness with breakage of fingernails or toenails.\n*''[[Paronychia]]'' is a [[bacterial]] or [[fungal]] [[infection]] where the nail and [[skin]] meet.\n*''[[Koilonychia]]'' is when the nail curves upwards (becomes spoon-shaped) due to an [[Iron deficiency (medicine)|iron deficiency]].  The normal process of change is: brittle nails, straight nails, spoon-shaped nails.\n*''[[Subungual hematoma]]'' occurs when trauma to the nail results in a collection of [[blood]], or [[hematoma]], under the nail.  It may result from an acute injury or from repeated minor [[Physical trauma|trauma]] such as running in undersized shoes.  Acute [[subungual hematoma]]s are quite painful, and are usually treated by releasing the [[blood]] by creating a small hole in the nail.  [[Drilling]] and [[cauterization|thermal cautery]]  are common methods for creating the hole.  Thermal cautery is not used on [[acrylic nails]] because they are [[flammable]].\n*''[[Onychomatricoma]]'', a tumor of the nail matrix.\n*''Nail [[Pemphigus]]'', an auto-immune disease.\n*''[[Longitudinal erythronychia|Erythronychia]]'', red bands in the nail from some inflammatory conditions.\n*''[[Melanonychia]]'', a black or brown discoloration of the nail, with numerous causes.\n\n==Nail changes and conditions associated with them==\nNail inspection can give hints to the internal condition of the body as well. \nNail disease can be very subtle and should be evaluated by a dermatologist with a focus in this particular area of medicine.  A nail technician may be the first to note a subtle change in nail health.<ref>Common nail tumors.\nBaran R, Richert B., Dermatol Clin. 2006 Jul;24(3):297-311. Review.</ref><ref>Dealing with melanonychia. Tosti A, Piraccini BM, de Farias DC. Semin Cutan Med Surg. 2009 Mar;28(1):49-54. Review.</ref><ref>The nail in systemic diseases. Tosti A, Iorizzo M, Piraccini BM, Starace M. Dermatol Clin. 2006 Jul;24(3):341-7. Review.</ref>\n\n===Pliability===\n*Brittleness is associated with iron deficiency, thyroid problems,<ref>[http://www.bhcs.com/healthinformation/baylorhealthmagazine/2005/nov/AS_thyroid.htm Baylor All Saints Medical Centers: Thyroid Disease<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and impaired kidney function.\n*Splitting and fraying are associated with [[psoriatic nails|psoriasis]] and deficiencies of [[folic acid]], protein, and [[Vitamin C|Vitamin&nbsp;C]].\n*Unusual thickness is associated with circulation problems.\n\n===Shape and texture===\n*[[Nail clubbing]] - nails that curve down around the fingertips with nailbeds that bulge is associated with oxygen deprivation and lung, heart, or liver disease.\n*[[Koilonychia]] - spooning, or nails that grow upwards. Associated with [[iron-deficiency anaemia]] or [[Vitamin B12 deficiency|vitamin B<sub>12</sub> deficiency]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n*Pitting of the nails is associated with [[psoriatic nails|psoriasis]].\n*[[Beau's lines]] are horizontal ridges in the nail.\n*[[Habit-tic deformity]] is a condition similar to Beau's Lines caused by long-term skin picking.\n\n===Discoloration of entire nail bed===\n*Yellowing of the nail bed is associated with chronic bronchitis, lymphatic problems, diabetes, and liver disorders.\n*Brown or copper nail beds are associated with [[arsenic poisoning|arsenic]] or [[copper poisoning]], and [[Onychomycosis|local fungal infection]].\n*Redness is associated with heart conditions.\n\n===Other color changes and markings===\n*[[Melanonychia]] (longitudinal streaking that darkens or does not grow out), especially on the thumb or big toe, may indicate subungual melanoma.\n*White lines across the nail ([[leukonychia]] striata, or transverse leukonychia) may be [[Mees' lines]] or [[Muehrcke's lines]].\n*Small white patches  are known as [[leukonychia]] punctata.\n*Dark nails are associated with B<sub>12</sub> deficiency.\n*Stains of the nail plate (not the nail bed) are associated with  smoking, and henna use.\n*[[Splinter hemorrhages]] (or haemorrhages) are tiny blood clots that tend to run vertically under the nails.\n*Drug-induced nail changes are caused by drug usage which may result in various abnormalities.<ref name=\"Fitz2\">Freedberg, et al. (2003). ''Fitzpatrick's Dermatology in General Medicine''. (6th ed.). McGraw-Hill. {{ISBN|0-07-138076-0}}.</ref>{{rp|665\u20136}}\n\n==Treatment==\nIn approximately half of suspected nail fungus cases there is actually no fungal infection, but only some nail dystrophy.<ref name=\"AADfive\">{{Citation |author1 = American Academy of Dermatology |author1-link = American Academy of Dermatology |date = February 2013 |title = Five Things Physicians and Patients Should Question |publisher = [[American Academy of Dermatology]] |work = [[Choosing Wisely]]: an initiative of the [[ABIM Foundation]] |page = |url = http://www.choosingwisely.org/doctor-patient-lists/american-academy-of-dermatology/ |accessdate = 5 December 2013}}, which cites\n*{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1046/j.1365-2133.2003.05242.x | last1 = Roberts | first1 = D. T. | last2 = Taylor | first2 = W. D. | last3 = Boyle | first3 = J. | author4 = British Association of Dermatologists | title = Guidelines for treatment of onychomycosis | journal = The British Journal of Dermatology | volume = 148 | issue = 3 | pages = 402\u2013410 | year = 2003 | pmid = 12653730}}\n*{{Cite journal | last1 = Mehregan | first1 = D. R. | last2 = Gee | first2 = S. L. | title = The cost effectiveness of testing for onychomycosis versus empiric treatment of onychodystrophies with oral antifungal agents | journal = Cutis | volume = 64 | issue = 6 | pages = 407\u2013410 | year = 1999 | pmid = 10626104}}</ref> Before beginning oral antifungal therapy the health care provider should confirm a fungal infection.<ref name=\"AADfive\"/> Administration of treatment to persons without an infection is [[unnecessary health care]] and causes needless exposure to side effects.<ref name=\"AADfive\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Hangnail]]\n* [[List of cutaneous conditions]]\n* [[Occupational hazards associated with exposure to human nail dust]]\n* [[Yellow nail syndrome]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Medical resources\n|   ICD10          = {{ICD10|L|60||l|60}}, {{ICD10|Q|84|3|q|80}}-{{ICD10|Q|84|6|q|80}} \n|   ICD9           = {{ICD9|703}}, {{ICD9|757.5}} \n|   ICDO           = \n|   OMIM           = \n|   MedlinePlus    = 003247 \n|   eMedicineSubj  = orthoped \n|   eMedicineTopic = 421 \n|   DiseasesDB     = 23092 \n|   MeshID         = D009260 \n}}\n{{Commonscat|Diseases and disorders of the nails}}\n*[https://www.cdc.gov/fungal/nail-infections.html Fungal Nail Infections] - explanation covering causes, treatment, and prevention\n*[http://hardinmd.lib.uiowa.edu/nailspictures.html Links to pictures of Nail Diseases (Hardin MD/Univ of Iowa)]\n*[http://www.aafp.org/afp/20040315/1417.html Nail Abnormalities: Clues to Systemic Disease]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150115061840/http://vikingrx.com/toenail-fungus-onychomycosis-treatment Links to pictures of Toenail Diseases (Wiggins MD)]\n\n{{Disorders of skin appendages}}\n{{Congenital malformations and deformations of skin appendages}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nail Disease}}\n[[Category:Conditions of the skin appendages]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Onychia|the squid genus|Onykia|the genus of moth|Onychia (moth)}}\n{{Infobox medical condition (new) \n| name            = Nail disease or disorder \n| image           = ONYCHIA1.JPG \n| caption         = Onychia without [[granuloma]] \n| \n| pronounce       =  \n| field           =  \n| synonyms        =  \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\nA '''nail disease''' or '''onychosis''' is a disease or deformity of the [[nail (anatomy)|nail]].  Although the nail is a structure produced by the skin and is a [[skin appendage]], nail diseases have a distinct classification as they have their own signs and symptoms which may relate to other medical conditions. Some nail conditions that show signs of [[infection]] or [[inflammation]] may require medical assistance.\n\n==Diseases==\n[[File:Human nail anatomy.jpg|thumb|Anatomy of the basic parts of a human nail. A. Nail plate; B. lunula; C. root; D. sinus; E. matrix; F. nail bed; G. eponychium; H. free margin.]]\n\n*''Onychia'' is an [[inflammation]] of the nail folds (surrounding tissue of the nail plate) of the nail with formation of [[pus]] and shedding of the nail.  Onychia results from the introduction of microscopic [[pathogen]]s through small wounds.\n*''[[Ingrown nail|Onychocryptosis]]'', commonly known as \"ingrown nails\" (''unguis incarnatus''), can affect either the fingers or the toes.  In this condition, the nail cuts into one or both sides of the [[nail (anatomy)#nail bed|nail bed]], resulting in [[inflammation]] and possibly [[infection]]. The relative rarity of this condition in the fingers suggests that [[pressure]] from the ground or shoe against the toe is a prime factor. The movements involved in [[walking]] or other physical disturbances can contribute to the problem.  Mild [[onychocryptosis]], particularly in the absence of infection, can be treated by trimming and rounding the nail.  More advanced cases, which usually include [[infection]], are treated by [[surgically]] excising the ingrowing portion of the nail down to its bony origin and [[thermally]] or [[chemically]] [[cauterizing]] the matrix, or 'root', to prevent recurrence.  This surgery is called [[matrixectomy]]. The best results are achieved by cauterizing the matrix with [[phenol]]. The [[Ingrown nail|Vandenbos Procedure]] is a highly effective method that focuses on excision of excessive nail fold tissue without affecting the healthy nail and nail matrix. The Vandenbos procedure is showing high success rates in eliminating Onychocryptosis without altering the normal nail. Another, much less effective, treatment is [[Surgery#excision|excision]] of the matrix, sometimes called a 'cold steel procedure'.[[File:Ingrown_nail_in_hallux_toe.jpg|thumb|Ingrown nail in hallux toe]]\n*''[[Onychodystrophy]]'' is a [[deformity|deformation]] of the nails that can result from cancer [[chemotherapy]] which includes [[bleomycin]], [[hydroxyurea]], or [[5-fluorouracil]]. It can include [[discoloration]] of the nail, or [[dyschromia]].\n*''[[Onychogryposis]]'', also called \"ram's-horn nail\", is a thickening and increase in [[curvature]] of the nail.  It is usually the result of injury to the matrix.  It may be partially [[hereditary]] and can also occur as a result of long-term neglect.  It is most commonly seen in the great [[toe]] but may be seen in other toes as well as the fingernails.  An affected nail has many grooves and ridges, is brownish in color, and grows more quickly on one side than on the other.  The thick curved nail is difficult to cut, and often remains untrimmed, exacerbating the problem.\n[[File:Onychomycosis.JPG|thumb|200px|[[Onychomycosis]] in every nail of the right foot.]]\n\n*''[[Onycholysis]]'' is a loosening of the exposed portion of the nail from the nail bed, usually beginning at the free edge and continuing to the [[lunula (anatomy)|lunula]].  It is frequently associated with an [[internal disorder]], [[Physical trauma|trauma]], [[infection]], [[nail fungi]], [[allergy]] to [[nail enhancement product]]s, or side effects of [[drug]]s.\n*''[[Onychomadesis]]'' is the separation and falling off of a nail from the [[nail (anatomy)#nail bed|nail bed]]. Common causes include localized [[infection]], minor injury to the [[matrix bed]], or severe [[systemic illness]]. It is sometimes a side effect of [[chemotherapy]] or [[x-ray]] treatments for [[cancer]]. A new nail plate will form once the cause of the disease is removed.\n*''[[Onychomycosis]]'', also known as [[tinea|''tinea unguium'']], is a contagious [[infection]] of the nail caused by the same [[fungal organism]]s which cause [[ringworm]] of the [[skin]] (''Trichophyton rubrum'' or ''T. mentagrophytes'', rarely other [[trichophyton]] species or ''Epidermophyton floccosum'' <ref name=\"mycology\">{{cite book |last= Hall |first= John C. |editor= John C. Hall |title= Sauer's Manual of Skin Diseases |edition= 9th |year= 2006 |publisher= Lippincott Williams & Wilkins |location= Philadelphia |isbn= 0-7817-2947-5|pages= 244=266 |chapter= 25. Dermatologic mycology.}}</ref>). It can result in [[discoloration]], [[thickening]], [[chalkiness]], or crumbling of the nails and is often treated by powerful oral medications which, rarely, can cause severe side effects including [[liver failure]]. Mild [[onychomycosis]] sometimes responds to a combination of [[topical]] [[antifungal medication]], sometimes applied as special [[medicinal]] nail [[lacquer]], and [[periodic filing]] of the nail surface. For advanced onychomycosis, especially if more than one nail is [[infection|infected]], systemic medication (pills) is preferred. Home remedies are often used, although their effectiveness is disputed.\n[[Image:HEMORRHAGESUBUNG1.JPG|thumb|right|Subungual hematoma (mild)]]\n*''[[Onychophosis]]'' is a growth of [[horn (anatomy)|horny]] [[epithelium]] in the nail.\n*''[[Onychoptosis]]'' is the periodic shedding of one or more nails, in whole or part. This condition may follow certain diseases such as [[syphilis]], or can result from [[fever]], trauma, [[systemic upset]]s or [[adverse reaction]] to drugs.\n*''[[Onychorrhexis]]'' also known as brittle nails, is brittleness with breakage of fingernails or toenails.\n*''[[Paronychia]]'' is a [[bacterial]] or [[fungal]] [[infection]] where the nail and [[skin]] meet.\n*''[[Koilonychia]]'' is when the nail curves upwards (becomes spoon-shaped) due to an [[Iron deficiency (medicine)|iron deficiency]].  The normal process of change is: brittle nails, straight nails, spoon-shaped nails.\n*''[[Subungual hematoma]]'' occurs when trauma to the nail results in a collection of [[blood]], or [[hematoma]], under the nail.  It may result from an acute injury or from repeated minor [[Physical trauma|trauma]] such as running in undersized shoes.  Acute [[subungual hematoma]]s are quite painful, and are usually treated by releasing the [[blood]] by creating a small hole in the nail.  [[Drilling]] and [[cauterization|thermal cautery]]  are common methods for creating the hole.  Thermal cautery is not used on [[acrylic nails]] because they are [[flammable]].\n*''[[Onychomatricoma]]'', a tumor of the nail matrix.\n*''Nail [[Pemphigus]]'', an auto-immune disease.\n*''[[Longitudinal erythronychia|Erythronychia]]'', red bands in the nail from some inflammatory conditions.\n*''[[Melanonychia]]'', a black or brown discoloration of the nail, with numerous causes.\n\n==Nail changes and conditions associated with them==\n\nNail inspection can give hints to the internal condition of the body as well. \nNail disease can be very subtle and should be evaluated by a dermatologist with a focus in this particular area of medicine.  A nail technician may be the first to note a subtle change in nail health.<ref>Common nail tumors.\nBaran R, Richert B.\n\nDermatol Clin. 2006 Jul;24(3):297-311. Review.\n</ref><ref>Dealing with melanonychia.\n\nTosti A, Piraccini BM, de Farias DC.\n\nSemin Cutan Med Surg. 2009 Mar;28(1):49-54. Review.\n</ref><ref>The nail in systemic diseases.\n\nTosti A, Iorizzo M, Piraccini BM, Starace M.\n\nDermatol Clin. 2006 Jul;24(3):341-7. Review.\n</ref>\n\n===Pliability===\n*Brittleness is associated with iron deficiency, thyroid problems,<ref>[http://www.bhcs.com/healthinformation/baylorhealthmagazine/2005/nov/AS_thyroid.htm Baylor All Saints Medical Centers: Thyroid Disease<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and impaired kidney function.\n*Splitting and fraying are associated with [[psoriatic nails|psoriasis]] and deficiencies of [[folic acid]], protein, and [[Vitamin C|Vitamin&nbsp;C]].\n*Unusual thickness is associated with circulation problems.\n\n===Shape and texture===\n*[[Nail clubbing]] - nails that curve down around the fingertips with nailbeds that bulge is associated with oxygen deprivation and lung, heart, or liver disease.\n*[[Koilonychia]] - spooning, or nails that grow upwards. Associated with [[iron-deficiency anaemia]] or [[Vitamin B12 deficiency|vitamin B<sub>12</sub> deficiency]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n*Pitting of the nails is associated with [[psoriatic nails|psoriasis]].\n*[[Beau's lines]] are horizontal ridges in the nail.\n*[[Habit-tic deformity]] is a condition similar to Beau's Lines caused by long-term skin picking.\n\n===Discoloration of entire nail bed===\n*Yellowing of the nail bed is associated with chronic bronchitis, lymphatic problems, diabetes, and liver disorders.\n*Brown or copper nail beds are associated with [[arsenic poisoning|arsenic]] or [[copper poisoning]], and [[Onychomycosis|local fungal infection]].\n*Redness is associated with heart conditions.\n\n===Other color changes and markings===\n*[[Melanonychia]] (longitudinal streaking that darkens or does not grow out), especially on the thumb or big toe, may indicate subungual melanoma.\n*White lines across the nail ([[leukonychia]] striata, or transverse leukonychia) may be [[Mees' lines]] or [[Muehrcke's lines]].\n*Small white patches  are known as [[leukonychia]] punctata.\n*Dark nails are associated with B<sub>12</sub> deficiency.\n*Stains of the nail plate (not the nail bed) are associated with  smoking, and henna use.\n*[[Splinter hemorrhages]] (or haemorrhages) are tiny blood clots that tend to run vertically under the nails.\n*Drug-induced nail changes are caused by drug usage which may result in various abnormalities.<ref name=\"Fitz2\">Freedberg, et al. (2003). ''Fitzpatrick's Dermatology in General Medicine''. (6th ed.). McGraw-Hill. {{ISBN|0-07-138076-0}}.</ref>{{rp|665\u20136}}\n\n==Treatment==\nIn approximately half of suspected nail fungus cases there is actually no fungal infection, but only some nail dystrophy.<ref name=\"AADfive\">{{Citation |author1 = American Academy of Dermatology |author1-link = American Academy of Dermatology |date = February 2013 |title = Five Things Physicians and Patients Should Question |publisher = [[American Academy of Dermatology]] |work = [[Choosing Wisely]]: an initiative of the [[ABIM Foundation]] |page = |url = http://www.choosingwisely.org/doctor-patient-lists/american-academy-of-dermatology/ |accessdate = 5 December 2013}}, which cites\n*{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1046/j.1365-2133.2003.05242.x | last1 = Roberts | first1 = D. T. | last2 = Taylor | first2 = W. D. | last3 = Boyle | first3 = J. | author4 = British Association of Dermatologists | title = Guidelines for treatment of onychomycosis | journal = The British Journal of Dermatology | volume = 148 | issue = 3 | pages = 402\u2013410 | year = 2003 | pmid = 12653730}}\n*{{Cite journal | last1 = Mehregan | first1 = D. R. | last2 = Gee | first2 = S. L. | title = The cost effectiveness of testing for onychomycosis versus empiric treatment of onychodystrophies with oral antifungal agents | journal = Cutis | volume = 64 | issue = 6 | pages = 407\u2013410 | year = 1999 | pmid = 10626104}}</ref> Before beginning oral antifungal therapy the health care provider should confirm a fungal infection.<ref name=\"AADfive\"/> Administration of treatment to persons without an infection is [[unnecessary health care]] and causes needless exposure to side effects.<ref name=\"AADfive\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{col div|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Beau's lines]]\n* [[Hangnail]]\n* [[Leukonychia]]\n* [[List of cutaneous conditions]]\n* [[Mees' lines]]\n* [[Occupational hazards associated with exposure to human nail dust]]\n* [[Yellow nail syndrome]]\n{{colend}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Refimprove|date=March 2008}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Medical resources\n|   ICD10          = {{ICD10|L|60||l|60}}, {{ICD10|Q|84|3|q|80}}-{{ICD10|Q|84|6|q|80}} \n|   ICD9           = {{ICD9|703}}, {{ICD9|757.5}} \n|   ICDO           = \n|   OMIM           = \n|   MedlinePlus    = 003247 \n|   eMedicineSubj  = orthoped \n|   eMedicineTopic = 421 \n|   DiseasesDB     = 23092 \n|   MeshID         = D009260 \n}}\n{{Commonscat|Diseases and disorders of the nails}}\n*[https://www.cdc.gov/fungal/nail-infections.html Fungal Nail Infections] - explanation covering causes, treatment, and prevention\n*[http://hardinmd.lib.uiowa.edu/nailspictures.html Links to pictures of Nail Diseases (Hardin MD/Univ of Iowa)]\n*[http://www.aafp.org/afp/20040315/1417.html Nail Abnormalities: Clues to Systemic Disease]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150115061840/http://vikingrx.com/toenail-fungus-onychomycosis-treatment Links to pictures of Toenail Diseases (Wiggins MD)]\n\n{{Disorders of skin appendages}}\n{{Congenital malformations and deformations of skin appendages}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nail Disease}}\n[[Category:Conditions of the skin appendages]]\n", "name_user": "Widefox", "label": "safe", "comment": "already in body perWP:SEEALSO/WP:OVERLINK, links perWP:CAPTION,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nail_disease"}
{"title_page": "George Halkidis", "text_new": "{{Infobox ice hockey player \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| played_for = [[Peoria Rivermen (ECHL)|Peoria Rivermen]] <br> [[HC Fassa]] <br> [[Ritten Sport]] <br> [[Wichita Thunder]] <br> [[Alleghe Hockey]] <br> [[Hull Stingrays]] <br> [[HC Eppan Pirates]] <br> [[IF Bj\u00f6rkl\u00f6ven]]\n| position = [[Defenceman (ice hockey)|Defense]]\n| shoots = Left\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 1\n| weight_lb = 209\n| ntl_team = CAN\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1982|6|18|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Newmarket, Ontario]], [[Canada|CAN]]\n| draft = Undrafted\n| draft_year = \n| draft_team = \n| career_start = 2003\n| career_end = 2011\n}}\n'''George Halkidis''' (born June 18, 1982 in [[Newmarket, Ontario]]) is a former [[Canadians|Canadian]] professional [[ice hockey]] player.  He is currently a Portfolio Manager at Richardson GMP.\n\n==Playing career==\nThe defencemen played in the [[Ontario Hockey League]] for the [[North Bay Centennials]] from 1999-2002.  He was then traded to the [[Kitchener Rangers]] during his overage season where he scored the game winner in the 2003 Memorial Cup Championship. He had 91 points in 252 OHL career games.\n\nHalkidis signed as a free agent by the [[St. Louis Blues]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL) in 2003 and played for the [[Peoria Rivermen (ECHL)|Peoria Rivermen]] of the ECHL in 2003-2004 where he was a plus 18 with 19 points in 65 games. During the 2004\u201305 lockout season, Halkidis went overseas to the Italian A league where he played for [[Val Di Fassa]] in 2004-2005 tallying 12 points in 32 games and Renon in 2005-2006 notching 27 points in 42 games. During the 2006-2007 season George came back to North America where he played for the [[Wichita Thunder]] of the Central Hockey League notching 29 points in 48 games. Halkidis returned to Europe for the 2007-2008 season, playing in Italy Series A with [[HC Alleghe]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/pdisplay.php?pid=50182 |title=George Halkidis |accessdate=August 6, 2010 |publisher=hockeydby.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009-2010, he played in the [[Elite Ice Hockey League]] with the [[Hull Stingrays]], where he had 7 goals, 15 assists for 22 points in 46 games. He has signed with the [[Eppan Pirates]] of the Italian A2 League for the 2010-2011 season. In February 2011 he signed for [[Bj\u00f6rkl\u00f6ven]] in the [[Sweden|Swedish]] division 1.\n\n==Career statistics==\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; width:60em\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\" \n! colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | \n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | \n! colspan=\"5\" | [[Regular season]] \n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | \n! colspan=\"5\" | [[Playoffs]] \n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\" \n! [[Season (sports)|Season]] \n! Team \n! League \n! GP \n! [[Goal (ice hockey)|G]] \n! [[Assist (ice hockey)|A]] \n! [[Point (ice hockey)|Pts]] \n! [[Penalty (ice hockey)|PIM]] \n! GP\n! G \n! A \n! Pts \n! PIM \n|- \n| [[1998\u201399 OPJHL season|1998\u201399]]\n| [[Newmarket Hurricanes]]\n| [[Ontario Junior Hockey League|OPJHL]]\n| 39 || 2 || 10 || 12 || 24\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-  bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[1999\u201300 OHL season|1999\u201300]]\n| [[North Bay Centennials]]\n| [[Ontario Hockey League|OHL]]\n| 66 || 2 || 3 || 5 || 15\n| 6 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[2000\u201301 OHL season|2000\u201301]]\n| North Bay Centennials\n| OHL\n| 58 || 3 || 15 || 18 || 31\n| 4 || 1 || 0 || 1 || 4\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2001\u201302 OHL season|2001\u201302]]\n| North Bay Centennials\n| OHL\n| 68 || 8 || 29 || 37 || 48\n| 5 || 0 || 3 || 3 || 6\n|-\n| [[2002\u201303 OHL season|2002\u201303]]\n| [[Kitchener Rangers]]\n| OHL\n| 60 || 10 || 21 || 31 || 64\n| 21 || 1 || 15 || 16 || 6\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2003\u201304 ECHL season|2003\u201304]]\n| [[Peoria Rivermen (ECHL)|Peoria Rivermen]]\n| [[ECHL]]\n| 65 || 5 || 14 || 19 || 22\n| 8 || 0 || 1 || 1 ||